notes: Also shpes(ë), shpezë.< *su-petno-t- (Huld, 1984: 154, in Kortlandt 1987).Alternatively, to pendë 'feather' < Lat. pinna, penna 'id.'. (Orel 429).
Borrowed from Latin familia. Also means 'family, spouse'.

Late derivative of ftoh ~ ftof 'to cool, to make cold' < Pr. Alb. *wi-tāja, whose second element compares with Slav. *tajo, *tajati 'to melt', < PIE *teh₂- 'thaw, melt', here with suffix -f- < -h- < *-sk̑e-. The oppositive meaning derives from the preverb f- < *wi- < *apu- (Schumacher & Matzinger: 974).
Borrowed from Lat venire. Aorist continues PAlb *erdza which is etymologically identical to Gk ερχομαι 'to come'.
Orel gives nëmëroj 'to number, to count'. Loan < Lat numerāre 'id'.
vdek = infin. Orel and Dyen claim Albanian-internal cognacy only. Holm offers < *dhguhei- 'to pass away, die'. cf. also Att Gk φθι-νω 'to die'.
Relatively late loanword from Lat canem or, rather, from its Balkan continuations, reflected in the lack of rhotacism in Tosk.
Also 'to suck'. piva (aor); pirë (participle). related to IE *po(i)- 'to drink'.
Related to IE *ous-, cf also Lat auris, Lith ausis, Latv auss.
(aor. stem reflects a different root PIE *gʷerh₃- + preverb *an-)
< IE *eh3uiom, cf. Arm jvoj (gen.) and Cze vejce. Orel, however, claims it to be a loan from Latin. Both have same etymological origin, however.
From IE *h3(e)kuih1 > PALb *atsiwi, a form of dual related to - inter alia - Skt aksi, Lith akì.

From PAlb *be(r)ja derived from IE *bher- 'to strike, to beat'. Aorist form rashë goes back to PAlb *rausa, a sigmatic aorist of IE *reu- 'to tear', cf also Skt ravate 'to smash', Lat ruo 'to tear', etc. (ra, ran = INF.)
Either (i) < PAlb *dzel-ma, from Alb dhallë 'buttermilk', or (ii) < IE *deh2- 'to flow' > all 3 Balkan IE languages, see also Gk cognate and Arm tamuk 'wet'.
Borrowed < Lat pinna, penna 'feather; pair of oxen'. Second meaning is a metaphoric derivative of the latter, meaning more 'plumage'.
< IE *gheres, cf. Skt haras 'flame, heat'. Etymologically identical also with Gk θερμος, Arm jerm.
< Rom *fluctulare, a modification of Lat fluctuare 'to move in waves, to move to and fro'.
kâmë ~ kâmbë Loan < Romance *camba ~ *gamba (but not attested in Balkan Romance) < (Vul)Lat gamba 'leg, ankle, pastern' (itself < Grk. κάμπη)

Inf = dhan. < PAlb *en-apa with filling hiatus, or from analogy with jam. Orel states this form to be parallel to IE *ap-/*ep- although Holm strongly disputes this. He claims no IE cognates outside Alb. Aor = dhase.
A singularised neut. plural PAlb *dara < IE *ghesr-, related to Gk χεîρ, Hitt. keššar, Toch A tsar-, Toch B sar-, Arm jern, all with identical meanings.
Together wirh Gr. κρᾱνίον, Ved. śīrṣṇá- going back to PIE *k̑roh₂sno- 'head'.
< Lat. intelligere 'to perceive'. More evident in dialect forms, such as this one (ndëgoj), Çamic endiglo and Old Geg (Buzuku) ëndiglonj.
Also 'middle'. A difficult word without any reliable explanation.
Old locative (orig. plural) of relative(-interrogative) që 'which, that'
gjuej besides (esp. older) gjuo(n)j and contracted gjuj.
Also (within NE Gheg) une, ūn(ë).Composite form of personal pronoun u (identical to u 'self' < PAlb *we) and particle në (cf. Gk ναí, νη).
From PAlb *awa-rautja, a prefix derivative based on IE *reu 'to tear, destroy': Skt rutá- 'broken', Lat ruo 'to fall down, to rush down' etc. INF = vra.
From PAlb *dija connected with IE *dhei(ə)- 'to see', cf Skt dhyā(ya)ti 'to observe, feel, think', Av dā(y)- 'to see'. INF = dit.
From PAlb *gadza. Etymologically connected with OHG questa 'tuft', PN kvistr 'branch'. Slav *gvozdb 'wood, forest'.
Borrowed < Rom *manctus, based on Lat mancus 'maimed, infirm', cf also Ital manca 'left hand'.
Also 'foot'. Borrowed < Rom *camba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.

'live, stay'; < Pr. Alb. *rānja-, which is connected by Orel with Lith. róju, róti 'to cope, be ready', thus pointing to a root PIE **reh₁i̯-, but connected with Alb, rri 'sit, stay' it could go back to *(h₁)rei̯d- 'lean', LIV 503, Matzinger & Schumacher 994, with different stem formation and preverb *an-.

Borrowed < Ital milza id., possibly even earlier < Goth *milti (cf Cat melsa) 'milt, spleen'. Suppletion zeze 'black' follows Trk usage of colours for entrails, cf karaciger 'liver' with kara 'black'.
From PAlb *dlata continuing IE *dlngh-to- and related to other IE adjectives for 'long'.
From PAlb *mērwa based on IE *mer- 'to die' as Gk φθειρ is based on φθειρω 'to destroy'. Holm claims this is hardly likely and prefers the IE origin *merh2- 'to squeeze' via PAlb mēr(e)n.
Borrowed from OHG gibūro 'peasant, villager', cf a similar source of Hung pór id < OBavar *pour.
From PAlb *miša further related to IE *memso-, cf also - inter alia - Skt māmsa-, Arm mis, Goth mimz, Slav *męso.
Identical with Lith. malà and Latv. mala 'bank, shore '. Also *mal- is reflected in ancient Balkan toponymy.
Borrowed < It gola id (?), made obvious by variant golë.
From PAlb *enmen- or *inmen-, etymologically close to OIr ainm, Slav *jbmę, PRus emnes, all meaning the same, and to other continuations of IE *(o)noHmn.
Borrowed < Turk. kafa 'occupit, head'. Poss. link with Lat. caput? Rum ceafă is an Albanian loanword!
Also 'young, recent'. From PAlb *rija < IE *er-, *or- 'to rise, to make move', cf ON orr 'quick', OS aru id, of similar origin.
From PAlb *nakti- corresponding to IE *nokut- > Skt nákt, Gk νυξ, Lat nox, etc, all with same meaning.
Goes back to PAlb *skun-tā derived from *skuna> hu.
From PAlb *nuka, cf such negatives in Skt naca, Lat nique, Goth nih, OIr na-ch, MW na-c, OBret na-c 'and not'.
From IE *sem- via Balkan-IE *sm-ijos > Arm mi, Gk μια and PAlb *mja. Orel disagrees, postulating an IE origin of *oi-no > Lat ūnus, Goth and OPrus ains, etc, all with identical meanings.
Goes back to PAlb *nera, further connected with Skt nár-, ανηρ (now husband), Arm ayr, all with identical meanings.
From PAlb *sūja, also connected with IE *sū- 'rain; to rain' and OPrus suge 'rain'.
Borrowed < Rom *rūga id, continuing Lat rūga 'wrinkle'.
Also 'oak'. From PAlb *wradnjā etymologically connected with Gk ραδιξ 'branch', Lat radix, Welsh gwraidd etc., all with same meaning.
Borrowed < Lat arēna id. Holm, however, prefers an alternative etymology < IE *er- 'sand, locker' (cf Lat rārus) but has no recent cognates.
From PAlb *sāksa, further connected to IE *seku- 'to follow, to see', Skt sácate 'to accompany, to follow', Gk επομαι, Lat sequor; also notably Goth saihvan 'to see'.
Adjectival derivative of of pref ~ preh < *për-eh with eh < Pr. Alb. *a(k)ska-, a *-ske/o- formation to PIE *h₂ek̑- 'sharp'.
Borrowed < Gmc *skurtaz 'short': OHG scurz, OE sceort 'id'.
Also 'to stand, to stay, to remain'. Goes back to PAlb *rina etymologically xlose to Skt rnóti 'to arise, to move', Gk ορνυμαι 'to move up' and related forms. See also /lexeme/929/.
Also 'hide, bark'. From PAlb *lauk-ura derived from IE *leuk- 'to shine, to be white''. Holm disagrees, proposing a form comprising the prefix lë- + kur = loan < Lat corium 'thick skin, leather'.
From PAlb *awa-leja, etymologically connected with Slav. *lĕjo, *lĕjati 'to doze, slumber'. Contested by Holm.

From PAlb *wāgla, *wāgra related to Lat vagor 'to roam around', OIr fán 'slope' < *uāg-no-. Originates semantically from 'to be crooked'. Holm, however, proposes a borrowing from Trk ufaklik 'tinyness' (< Arab faqīr 'poor').
Continues PAlb *ātuma connected with Gmc *ēdumaz 'breath' and further related to Skt ātmán- 'blow, breath, soul'. Holm argues it is a loan < Gk θνμος from IE *dhueh2-.
Also 'to sit, to stay, to remain'. Goes back to PAlb *rina etymologically close to Skt rnóti 'to arise, to move', Gk ορνυμαι 'to move up' and related forms. See also /lexeme/916/.
Goes back to PAlb *skīw-ila, derived from *skijā > hije 'shadow' (Orel). Holm, however, prefers an IE origin in *h1eus 'burn, glow'.
Also 'rock'. From PAlb *gura continuing IE *guer- 'mountain', cf Skt gir-, Av gairi-, Lith girià 'wood', Latv dziria id and Slav *gora 'mountain, wood'.

Orel gives the old idea of a derivation from PIE *g̑ʰelh₃-u̯o- 'yellow', but Holm (p. 82) suggests alternatively to put it back to PIE *dei̯h₂- (LIV 108) 'blaze, shine', viz. *d(e)i̯h₂-lo-, cf. Alb. ditë 'day(light)' < *dih₂-to-.
Nasal lost secondary after the aorist; frequent in the same meaning non-active âjem.
Loan < Rom *notāre, replacing ClLat natāre, same meaning. Holm prefers notim 'swimming' < IE snéh2-timo, cf Gk νηχω id.

Also he and she, respectively. Goes back to PAlb *a-ei, comprising (i) a deictic element (*a), and (ii) a demonstrative pronoun (-i, -jo, -ta) which may represent a conflation of PIE *so, -to with the anaphoric pronoun *e/i-.

Masculine and feminine forms, respectively. Composed of two parts derived from: (i) PAlb *ka-/*kë (acc to Orel a pronominal element, acc to Kortlandt < Lat eccum), and (ii) demonstrative pronouns -i, -jo which represent a conflation of PIE demonstratives *so-, *to- with anaphoric pronoun *e/i-.
Alternative (so in Dyen) shtij/shtie has a more specialized meaning 'cast, shoot, project into sth.' (cf. e.g. Mann 1948 s.v.).

From PAlb *glusā, further connected with IE dial. *golso- 'sound', cf also ON kall 'shout', Lith galsas 'echo', Slav golsъ 'voice'. Holm disagrees, favouring instead a root in IE *dnghuā 'tongue', cf /cognate/327/(cognate class W).
From PAlb *dzamba, a dialectal IE word for tooth shared with TochA, TochB, Latv, Slav, etc. Original meaning is preserved in Gk γομφος and Skt jámbha- 'peg'.
Also 'wood'. From PAlb *druwa < PIE dru(-n) etymologically compared with Slav drъvo 'wood', Skt dru- id., Av dru- id., etc.
Also used in the form ç'. From PAlb *tši continuing IE *kuid.
From PAlb *kur formally identical with Arm ur, Lith kur 'where', Latv kùr id., derived from IE *kuu.

From PAlb *bardza continuing *bhorəgo-, a derivative of IE *bhereg- 'to shine; white', cf Skt bhrājate '(he) shines, beams, glitters', Goth bairhts 'light, shining' and the word for birch: Lith bérzas, Slv *berza.
From PAlb *kuša going back to IE *kuu-so consisting of *kuu- and demonstrative *so-. The form is thus quite close to TochA kus, TochB kuse, both with identical meanings.
North Eastern Geg: Kosovo;Loan < Turkish sarı 'yellow'. The Standard word verdhë denotes 'green'.
Apparently from կուռն kowṙ-n 'back' + -ակ -ak (forming diminutives from nominal stems).
Traditionally, խած- xac- is derived from *kʰad-i̯e- (cf. Ved. khādati 'chew, bite'). Cf. also խոտ xot 'grass' /cognate/593/.
կիթ kitʿ"(act of collecting) animal product(s)", such as 'milk(ing)', 'butter', '(collecting) eggs', etc.
Suppletive past stem: ինկա- ink-a-; cf. CA անկա- ank-a- (with a later alternative form ընկա-  ənk-a-) 'id.'.
Denominative of (CA) կռիւ kṙiw 'fight, strife; uproar'.

Linked with Skt. meghá- m. 'cloud, gloomy weather', Av. maēɣa- m. 'cloud', Gr. ὀμίχλη 'mist, fog', Lith. miglà 'fog', Dutch dial. miggelen 'staubregnen', etc. Other scholars consider it a loan < Iranian.
From a Proto-Armenian compound of *mit-a- 'mind' (< PIE *mēd-es-h₂; cf. Gk. μῆδος) and *ac-e- 'drive; lead' (< PIE h₂eg̑-e/o-).
Apparently a by-form of քայլել kʿayl-e-l, the original denominative of քայլ kʿayl 'step'; cf. also a dialectal by-form քելել  kʿel-e-l 'id.'.
nAF: KUṘN, < 'curved, crooked body part' < Arm. KOR 'curved, crooked', cogn. with 'turn' in /cognate/3063/; ultimate cognate of /cognate/2183/?

From Old (= Classical) Armenian որովհետեւ orovhetew 'since; whereas' (possibly analyzable as or-o-v+het-e-w 'by/with which step', in which the second element may be transposed onto PIE *ped-e-to-s, an ablatival formation, lit. "from [which] step on", cf. Ved. patsutas lit. "from [a place] at the feet", Lat. funditus 'completely'; orig. "from the bottom [up]").
Cf. passivized այրվել ayr-v-e-l 'to burn, i.e. to be consumed by fire'.

gloss: specifically 'human child; young human being, infant'

notes: doubtfully connected with IE *bheugh- 'bend' > 'with bent point'
hoł fr. IE *pela-? , connected to 'wide' in /cognate/667/, Lat. PALAM 'overt, publictly' and OCS POLJE 'field'
Loan < Iranian. Cf. MPers clp' 'mild gentle; fatty, oily' and MParth crb 'smooth, mild'.
Phonemically, however, /d͡zuk-n-/; cf. Nom. Pl. ձկներ d͡zkn-er, Inst. Sg. ձկնով d͡zkn-ov, (with a morphophonological reduction of /u/), etc.
Apparently a compound of այս ay-s (see /cognate/6052/) and տեղի tełi 'place'; cf. այնտեղ ay-n-teł 'there', /lexeme/1923/.

gloss: Also 'attach, fasten, nail; fire, shoot; (dial.) cover, shut, close'
notes: Also 'attach, fasten, nail; fire, shoot; (dial.) cover, shut, close'

gloss: both stative and inchoative, i.e. 'to lie down'

notes: Cognate with /cognate/53/ 'head' although some scholars believe the term to be a loan < Iranian, cf MPers sl, ManMPers, MParth sr 'eahd'; top, summit; end, Av sarah- 'head'.
prob. connected to HATANEM 'to cut', further etym. dub., mabye  IE *peu- 'to hit' as in Lat. PAVIO?
Loan < Syr meškā 'skin, leather' or MPers mšk' 'skin bag (for liquids)'.
OMN 'who' < IE *kwo-, thus the same as in /cognate/339/
Apparently a compound of այն ay-n (see /cognate/6052/) and տեղի tełi 'place'; cf. այստեղ ay-s-teł 'here', /lexeme/1834/.
From a Proto-Armenian compound of *mit-a- 'mind' (< PIE *mēd-es-h₂; cf. Gk. μῆδος) and *ac-e- 'drive; lead' (< PIE h₂eg̑-e/o-).
Martirosyan relates to Gr. THALLO 'to bloom' and  'leaf' in /cognate/1025/
Alternative lexemes are 'понеже, тъй так, затова че'. They seem too be less frequently used.
An alternative lexeme is 'рия' which, however, refers normally to digging with the foot or muzzle.
An alternative lexeme is 'tatko' which is, however, judged as colloquial. 'отец' in the meaning 'father' is obsolete; the word is used today in the religious meaning only.
Most frequently used (judgement of a native speaker).
Alternative lexemes are: 'шнур' (rather 'thick rope'), 'канап' (rather 'thin rope'), and 'връв' (rather 'thin rope').
An alternative lexeme is 'търкам' (with the same root?).
'кратък' is used in temporal meaning ('short time'), for distances ('short way'), and in the meaning 'brief'.
Alternative lexeme are 'бозая' and 'суча'. However, they refer rather only to suckling while 'смуча' seems to have a more general meaning.
Depending on the context an alternative phonetic form 'ўсе' is used.
Alternative lexemes are 'кепскі' and 'благі'. They seem to have a more restricted usage. At least normally 'дрэнны' is given on the first place in dictionaries.
An alternative lexeme is 'птах' with the same root.
An alternative form is a diminutive 'костка' with meaning 'single bone'.
An alternative lexeme 'рыць' is used for animals.
An alternative lexeme is 'глеба', but it is rather something like 'soil'.
An alternative lexeme is 'яйцо', with the same root.
An alternative lexeme is 'кішкі'; it seems to be less general than 'вантробы' which refers to any or all internal body organ(s).

Depending on the context alternative phonetic forms 'ў, ва, ува' are used (to some extent the choice is orthographic too). In the local meaning with the Locative case all this forms are cognates of *vъ. Do not mix it with another, different preposition *u!
1. I pushed my brother into a hole.2. He pushed the door to enter the house.Perfective: 'пхнуць'.
An alternative lexeme is 'шлях'. Sources seem to prefere 'дарога' and 'шлях' is given often in more abstract/figurative contexts or in (professional) terms.
Alternative lexemes are 'матуз', 'ліна' 'аборка'. 'вяроўка' seems to be the most general word.
In some contexts a reflexive form 'чухацца' is used. With an irregular (expressive) change -s- > -x- and an irregular vowel change.
An alternative lexeme is 'семя', historically with the same root.
An alternative lexeme is: 'петь', with the same root (at least historically).
An alternative lexeme is 'малы', with the same root.
This verb is used for passive 'smelling' ('perceiving the odour') only. By active action ("she smelled the vegetables before cooking them") only 'нюхаць' is used.
An alternative lexeme is 'вужака', but it it can mean also / it is rather 'grass snake'.
In contexts like: 'He hurt is arm, then it started to swell'.
An alternative lexeme 'мысліць' is used in more philosophical meaning.
Depending on the context various prefixes or reflexive forms can be used.
Removed final -S. From Latin spatula 'flat piece, shoulder blade'. Really means 'shoulder'.
from the notion of 'above, on' SUR?
Replaced TRAURER, TIRAR. 'to take, pull, draw out (from)'.
Romance terms fr. ECCU+ISTE, ECCU = root of /cognate/2437/ + -CE 'here, there' /cognate/2435/, ISTE = IS (again root of /cognate/2437/) + root of /cognate/323/)
'bind, tie together'. Delinked from cognate class C.
An alternative lexeme is 'i' but it has an additional meaning (it is described as "stronger" than 'a').
An alternative lexeme is 'mrak', but it means 'black, rain cloud'.
An alternative lexeme is 'chladný' but its meaning is more like 'cool' ore something between 'cold' and 'cool'.
An alternative lexeme is 'rýt' but in contextes like in the "Description" the verb 'kopat' is used.
An alternative lexeme is 'útroby', but it is bookish.
An alternative lexeme is 'honit' but 'hunt' is only one of its meaning and not the main one.
An alternative lexeme is 'huba'. It is widely used but dictionaries of Standard Czech judge it as expressive or colloquial.
Meaning: 'not this one, but a different one'
In some contextes a form 'hrat *si*' is used.
Alternative lexemes are 'šňůra', 'lano' but they have more specified meanings: 'strong rope and/or long rope'.
Refers to food. 'zpráchnivělý, práchnivý' refers to powdery, rotting trees or wood.
In some contexts a reflexive form 'škrábat se' is used.
An alternative lexeme is 'onen' but it has additional meaninigs.
2. I turned my head suddenly when I heard the loud noise.
An alternative lexeme is 'blít' but it is expressive.

Consequently note that in HED H the forms are found under the stem ḫurnai- / ḫurniya-, but in HW² Ḫ under ḫarnai-, ḫarniya-.

Alternative lexemes are 'овъ' and 'и'. However, 'овъ' is rare in the meaning 'that' (and it can mean also 'this') and 'и' is used only in relative constructions.
Alternative lexemes are 'овъ' and 'и'. However, 'овъ' is rare in the meaning 'that' (and it can mean also 'this') and 'и' is used only in relative constructions.

It can refer also to a motion. There are some alternative lexemes. 'тамо' has the same meaning(s) but its less frequent used (40 times vs >300 <400 times). 'онъде' is attested only once. 'овъде' is relatively rare too (6 times) and it is used only in a comparing construction 'here..., there...'.
The word is reconstructed on the base of an attested derivatives (like 'дебельство'). However, it is not entirely clear if the meaning is 'thick' or rather 'fat'.
The vowel difference in the stem reflexes probably a dialectal variation. For the OCS proper the 'тьнъкъ' form was probably typical.

An alternative lexeme is 'овъ'. However, its meaning can vary or is something between 'this' and 'that' and it is rarely used as a separate pronoun (it is rather used in contructions like 'this..., other...'.
There was possibly a dialectal variant 'тєплъ' (-e- in attested in the Canon in derivatives).

'лѣсъ' is attested twice in the Canon. There are alternative lexemes: 'дрѧзга' (attested once as 'woods, grove, coppice'), 'дѫбрава' (attested five times as 'grove, coppice, oak woods, deciduous forest') and 'лѫгъ' (attested once as 'woods, grove, coppice').

An alternative lexeme is 'годъ'. However, it attested only once in the Canon. Both words have other original meaning which seem to be stil primary in the OCS time: 'лѣто' is 'summer', 'годъ' is 'appropriate, appointed time'.

The word 'жльтъ' is not attested in OCS. However, the derivative 'жльтѣница' 'a kind of plant with yellow flowers' and the contaminated form 'жльчь' (instead of / alongside зльчь) 'gall' show that such an adjective did exist. An alternative lexeme is 'плавъ' but it has a more specific meaning 'fair, fawn, colour of ripe cereals'.
sceran is "cut" in the sense "shear, clip, shave", not "incise, cut into""
This is a variant form of the adjective "afraid, timid"
This is "do battle", and is poetic
The non-metathesised form græs (as in IELex1) is attested, but gærs is more frequent
Appears to mean specifically "intestine" or "fibre" (and "gut" prepared as a string)
A more common word, but meaning is chiefly "bind, restrain, tie up"
Only attested for washing clothes or sheep.
Damp/moist, not wet. = Du. VOCHT(IG), NHG FEUCHT 'wet, damp'
borrowed into MEng.: illNot the default for 'bad', but more of a moral sense.
Really does refer to the internal organ, but a better fit than anything else.
The form formerly here is the past participle of the verb 'to make dirty, shit on'.
‘cloud of dust as caused by tramp of horses’, cf. /lexeme/21773/lit. 'horse smoke'

noun, AF feita; mostly attested in compounds
Choice of this or hræðask is stylistic (frequencies vary between authors, but not as a whole)
Unable to find this in the meaning 'float'
Does not appear in any other source. cognate with 'tail' in /cognate/1070/

notes: refers to the long bone of either the arm or the leg; in later texts to the thigh, but never the entire limb.
also ‘old man, man of lower rank'
primarily used of non-edible flesh, e.g. 'flesh and bone'
as of shirt, room, opp. of  víðr, AF o̜ngr
AF skýfirChanged spelling -- spelling skúfa only exists in one compound TKD
comparative form of hœgr 'easy/convenient', usually accompanied by the preposition til when meaning 'to the right'
with fingernails', AF klóra (also ‘scratch, tear with fingernails or claws’)
Ringe et al. gives these as separate termsAlso sjár (rare)
Ringe et al. gives only sér
only of boats, ultim. cognate, but in the sense of ‘sew’ early loan word from Danish, AF saumar
more than a couple rather than some of a group
from noun hráki, see note on /cognate/1401/ and on /lexeme/17992/
of sea, body part, AF svellr

of the same paradigm of sá, but neut. sg. (not dictionary citation form)

refers to tree or substance 'wood', only secondarily to a collection of trees
acc., related to lith.: vargas 'miserable', Old Church Slav.: vrag 'enemy'
Third Catechism, acc.pl. EV: pepelis. Gr: pipelko
Third Catechism inf. Basel epigram: poyt
related to many terms for 'child, son', e.g. /cognate/1462/
EV, animal fat for cooking and to spread on bread
EV, fat in the human body
Third Catechism. EV: towis. Gr: taus
somebody, some’, related to 'one' in /cognate/91/?, see also /cognate/2946/
AV ~ bhásma n. AV+ SHOULD BE EARLY VEDIC SWADESH TERM, on which see /cognate/2189/.The Sanskrit word is a thematicized form from the full grade stem of the PIE root noun.
cf. médas- n. 'fat, marrow' (*fat inside body)
root; more frequent in RV than denominative verbs from pr̥t- 'fight'
obl. hr̥d-; EARLY SWADESH TERM, ~ hŕ̥dayam
~ naktán- n., nákti- f., nák- f.
Kāṭh.+, i.e. not relly Early Vedic
attested only once in the RV, while taptá- is more frequent - really the target?
pl. ā́pas; VEDIC SWADESH TERM! (= clearly more frequent than) ~vā́r ~ váar n.
'wide, extensive, broad, extended, spacious, roomy; not narrow'
'wide, extensive, flat and broad, large, flat and extended, flat and roomy'
~ pátram n. ~ pátatram ~ parṇám n.; see 'feather'
pont- obl. form of A puk B po
related to OHG lûs, Skt. yûkâ- 'louse'
Locative agglutinative case affix, with the meaning INESSIVE.
Etymology uncertain; derived from umpar 'evil' (umpar yām- 'commit an evil deed'), hence probably more specifically 'evil'.
comp. of KU (common IE pron.) + YA 'to do'

Etymology unclear; perhaps ultimately from *dʰóbʰu- ~ *dʰébʰu- 'little piece, bit' > 'large piece, chunk' (cf. Hitt. tēpu- 'little'; R. Kim 2019: 183-184)? Suppletive pl. śāwe originally 'coarse, rough; made of large pieces', cf.TB aśāwe, TA āśāwe 'coarse, rough, horrible' (R. Kim 2019: 181-183).
Root unclear; attested only pres. 3sg. piwāṣ and pret. ptcp. pāpeyu. Related to Lat. spīrāre < *(s)pey-, or is latter onomatopoeic?
Probably not haplology from PT du. *pəścənë-në 'breasts' (Ringe 1996:71), given archaic TB acc. pl. pastäṃ* (Adams 2013:386); morphological details unclear.
Root /wrs-/; cf. derivative wrasom 'living being', lit. 'breathing one'; from PIE *u̯er- 'perceive'.
Root /krṣtā-/, alternating with /kraṣtā-/ in the subjunctive.
Root /wl-/; not cognate with Toch. B /srəwka-/; cf. however causative sruk- 'kill'.

Root /yok-/. Possibly from Narten present of *h₁eh₂gʷʰ- (Kim 2000); generally derived from Narten present of *h₁egʷʰ-. Non-pres. stems formed to a suppletive stem /ʦukā-/, alternating with /ʦokā-/ in the subj. and pret. and /śukā-/ in the pret.; probably from PIE *dʰewgʰ-.
Exact meaning and contrast with tor unclear; cf. Toch. B taur and tweye.
Du. klośäṃ, cf. Toch. B klautsane.
Cf. Toch. B tkeṃ (archaic), keṃ with cluster simplification.
Root /klāwā-/, contracted to /klā-/ in most nonpres. forms; pres. /klaw-a-/. Wider connections unclear.
Exact relationship to Toch. B puwar unclear; probably contracted from PIE sg. *peh2-u̯r̥
Root /plu-/, attested only in ptcp. plumāṃ and pret. pl. plawar.
Ultimately from a derivative *pod-yo-; cf. Toch. B paiyye. Du. peṃ., pl. peyu, peñ* (acc. pes).

Suppletive stem krant-.  Originally a participle to *ĝʰer- 'find favor with' (van Windekens 1976:232), rather than *gʷerh₂- 'approve' (Pinault 1979:349); note unique survival of intraparadigmatic ablaut in fem. kräṃts* (kräts).
Attested in acc. āti, pl. ātyāñ.
Hapax loc. pl. weṣkiñcāsaṃ (A124 b4); meaning uncertain.
Probably from *śəṣə́rə < PIE acc. *g̑ʰés-r-m̥, though details and exact relationship to Toch. B ṣar unclear.
Synchronically locative of n. täṣ 'this', near-deixis demonstrative (see below, THIS).
Root /krn-/; morphologically causative. Wider connections uncertain.
Cf. Toch. B krorīya*. Generally taken from the family of *k̂rh₂sn- 'horn', but Hilmarsson (1985) compares Toch. B krorīya with Arm. ełǰiwr < PIE *g̑ʰréh₁-u̯r̥.
Etymology much debated, but ultimately connected with PIE obl. *me-. Cf. Toch. B ñäś, ñiś 'I' (both genders).
Root /knā-/, cf. Toch. B /nana-/ 'appear'. Significantly less common than /krsā-/, but no clear evidence for secondary or restricted value; also clearly inherited.
Root /krsā-/, alternating with /karsā-/ in subjunctive and preterite and /śrsā-/ in preterite.
Root /kar-/, pres. /kare-/ ~ /karya-/ with unique and partially unexplained stem alternation.
Less common than oṅk, without etymology or Toch. B cognate.
Synchronically gerundive of /śwā-/ 'eat', hence 'meat' < *'that which can be eaten'.
The vocalism points to PIE acrostatic *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥ > PToch. *ñemə, but other cognates are consistent with a proterokinetic paradigm.
In declarative clauses only (vs. prohibitive mar); cf. Toch. B mā in both senses.

Fossilized pret. ptcp. of /oks-/ 'grow, age' (cf. Toch. B aukṣu); replaced in the verbal paradigm with okṣiññu to the innovative nonpres. stem okṣiññ-. Toch. A ktsets, cognate with Toch. B ktsaitse 'old', preserves the original meaning 'perfect, accomplished'.
Fem. säṃ (cf. Toch. B sana); otherwise suppletive stem ṣom- (e.g. masc. pl. ṣome, cf. Toch. B ṣemi).
Root /ʦkā-/, alternating with /ʦakā-/ in the preterite.
Final -e unexpected; influenced by Toch. B swese?
Cf. Toch. B śwālyai 'id.'; fossilized gerundive to śwā- 'eat' (from an apparent ablaut variant *śāwā-), hence '(hand) for eating'.
Derived from /ʦmā-/ 'grow'; replaced cognate of Toch. B witsako, itself an Iranian borrowing?
The less common sārm may have a more general term, 'that which is sown'.

Root /lmā-/, alternating with /lamā-/ in the subj. and pret. and /lʲmā-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /ṣm(a)-/. Pres. widely taken to be from PIE *sed- with *m of nonpres. stem, but source of latter itself disputed.
Root /wr-/. Intransitive; no transitive pres. forms attested.
Root /ṣtmā-/, alternating with /ṣtamā-/ in the subj. and pret. and /śmā-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /klʲ(ə)-/.
Synchronically locative of neut. täm, far-deixis demonstrative (see above, THAT).
Masc. pl. of säm 'that', see THAT.
Inherited pattern of suppletion faithfully preserved. Cognate with Toch. B se, sā, te, with addition of deictic particle.
Root /wrt-/, attested only in pret. wort*, worta-ṃ. Morphological causative of 'turn', cf. Toch. B /wərt-/ 'turn', but details and wider affiliations unclear.
Root /krk-/, attested only in subj. and pret.
Root /spārtwā-/, irregular pres. act. /sparcw(a)-/ beside mid. /sparcw-a-/.
Fem. we, cognate with Toch. B wi (both genders).
Root /klkā-/, alternating with /kalkā-/ in the subjunctive and preterite; suppletive pres. stem /y-/.
Ultimately cognate with PIE *u̯ód-r̥, but details unclear.
Also acc. 'us'. Crossing of nom. *weys and obl. *nos.
Relative äntā-ne 'when'. Cf. Toch. B ente.
'With X' is usually expressed by the comitative case alone (TA X-aśśäl).
Generally derived from an n-stem derivative of PIE *gʷen- with dissimilation of *n > *l by the following nasal (see Pinault 2005, Fs Gercenberg), but many details remain unclear.
Probably borrowed from Khotanese; see DTTA:115.
The less common kārāś has the more general meaning of 'forest, woods, wilderness'. Cf. Toch. B karāś.
Also acc. 'you (pl.)'. Crossing of nom. *yuHs and obl. *wos.
Phonetic labiovelar suggested by spellings such as pl. puklā, pᵤklā.
Locative agglutinative case affix, with the meaning INESSIVE
Attractive etymological connection with Hitt. idālu-, Luv. ādduwāl(i)- from PIE *h₁éd-wōl (Peyrot).
rfcWebLookup1: Toch. B pakwāre has the more specialized meaning of 'evil'.

notes: Perfect semantic match in Hittite and Hieroglyphic Luvian ura- ‘great’ (van Windekens 1960, Melchert apud Adams 2013:128), but the phonological details are unclear. Toch. B māka (cf. Toch. A māk) means 'much, many'.
From PIE collective **h1esh2-ōr > *h1ésh2-ōr; see also Toch. A ysār.
Root /pəyn-/. Related to Lat. spīrāre < *(s)pey-, or is latter onomatopoeic?
Suppletive pl. āsta; pace Stalmaszczyk and Witczak (1990:40-1) and Katz (1997:72-7), āy probably not from PIE *h₂ést by a rule of *-s > *-y in monosyllables.
Probably not haplology from PT du. *pəścənë-në 'breasts' (Ringe 1996:71); archaic acc. pl. pastäṃ* (loc. pä[s]tänne) points to sg. paśce* (Adams 2013:386).
Pl. śamaskañ often 'children'; cf. śamñāṃśka 'girl', likewise derived from śaumo, pl. śāmna 'person', śāmñe 'human'.
Root /ṣəns-/, pres. stem /ṣənṣ-ə-/ ~ /ṣəns-e-/. < IE *sems-, = Ice SEMJA 'to put together, unite'
Root /kərsta-/, alternating with /krasta-/ in the subjunctive.
Root /latka-/; pres. stem attested only in impf. 3pl. latkanoyeñ-c, beside synchronically irregular (hence presumably archaic) lyecciṃ to stem /lʲecc-ə-/ ~ /lʲetk-e-/.
Root /srəwka-/, alternating with /srawka-/ in the subjunctive; pres. stem /srəwk-e-/. Not cognate with Toch. A /wl-/; cf. Toch. A /sruk-/ 'kill'.
Root /rapa-/; nasal pres. replacement for PToch. root pres. *rəpa-, cf. Toch. A rpā-, inf. rpātsi.
Synchronically derived from krāke 'dirt, filth'. The rare sal may have a more specialized meaning 'impure'.
Root /jok-/. Possibly from Narten present of *h₁eh₂gʷʰ- (Kim 2000); generally derived from Narten present of *h₁egʷʰ-.
Exact meaning uncertain; usually occurs together with taur 'dust, ashes'.
Du. klautsane, cf. Toch. A klośäṃ.
Original initial consonant cluster preserved in Toch. A in archaic tkeṃ and Toch. A tkaṃ

All forms made to the root /śəwa-/ except for preterite participle śeśu*, which presupposes a root /śəw-/; subj. 1sg. śū (PK NS 58 b2) may be an error for expected śuwau (Peyrot 2013:484, pace Pinault 1994b:170-82).
Du. eśane; older eś in yn-eś 'evident', eś lmau 'blinded', lit. 'sat (on) the eyes'.
Root /pərska-/, alternating with /praska-/ in the subjunctive and (exceptionally) present. Remodeled from (post-)PIE *pṛK-sḱé/ó-, cf. GERMANIC.
Root /wəjta-/, to judge from weta 'struggle' and other derivatives. Apparent subj. /wə́ta-/ in v.n. watalyñe unclear. Possibly simply /wəjt-tər/.
From *ph₂u̯ōr ← PIE collective *péh₂-u̯ōr; see also Toch. A por.
Possible very early borrowing from an IE language of eastern Europe (Balto-Slavic, Ringe 1996:92); for other connections, see Adams 2013:590.
Loss of nasal between pre-TB *i and sibilant regular here and in mīsa; see MEAT.
related to Toch RÄS- 'to enlarge, lenghten, stretch'? (Windekens 1976: 82)
Etymology unknown; cf. Toch. A pyāpyi
Root /pləw-/, alternating with /plʲew-/ in the subj. and pret.

Ultimately from a derivative *pod-yo-, though the exact source of the unusual sequence -aiy- is unclear; the unextended noun survives in -pew '-footed' < PIE *pod-w(e)nt- and perhaps du. paine. See Kim 2018:80–1.
Fem. kartsa, otherwise suppletive stem krent-. Originally a participle to *ĝʰer- 'find favor with' (van Windekens 1976:232), rather than *gʷerh₂- 'approve' (Pinault 1979:349).
Attested only in acc. atiyai, pl. atiyañ; usually attested in plural.
Plurale tantum; cognate with Latv. mats?
From PToch. *śəṣə́rə < PIE acc. *g̑ʰés-r-m̥ with contraction. Exact relationship with TA tsar uncertain, though most scholars derive them from the same PIE source.
Diphthong /ew/ is preserved as ew, eu in early texts.
Toch. B pl. käryāñ (IOL Toch 1 a4) continues PIE *k̂erd-, cf. Toch. A kri 'will'.
Cf. Toch. A kärn- 'id.' Toch. B /pyak-/ has a similar but more specific meaning 'strike (down), beat (a drum)'.
Attested in acc. krorīyai; cf. Toch. A kror 'crescent'. Generally taken from the family of *k̂rh₂sn- 'horn', but Hilmarsson (1985) compares Arm. ełǰiwr < PIE *g̑ʰréh₁-u̯r̥.
Cf. mant 'so', Toch. A mänt 'as; how', mäntne 'so, thus'.

Only form attested. Claimed loanword from Indo-Iranian, but just as likely inherited; denominative to śerwe 'hunter' (cf. Toch. A śaru). Latter prob. a vrddhi-derivative of PIE *k̂erwo- 'stag' (Jasanoff apud Nussbaum 1986:8), rather than **g̑ʰu̯ēr-u- (so Adams 2013:694).
Etymology much debated, but probably ultimately connected with PIE *me-, obl. stem of 1sg. pronoun. Cf. Toch. A näṣ (m.), ñuk (f.).
Attested only in dual; extended form with productive du. ending -ne attested in IOL Toch 210 b3 and adj. kenine-ṣṣe ‘pertaining to the knees’ (cf. Toch. A kanweṃ).

Root /ajk-/, pres./subj. stem /ajɕ-ə-/ ~ /ajk-e-/. Meaning very similar to that of /kərsa-/ (not clearly distinguished like Ger. wissen vs. kennen, Fr. savoir vs. connaître, or Pol. wiedzieć vs. znać), but rather 'know, recognize'; note Toch. B po-aiśi, poyśi 'the All-Knowing' (epithet of the Buddha).
Root /kərsa-/, alternating with /karsa-/ in the subjunctive and /śərsa-/ in the preterite.
Root /ker-/, pres. stem /kerəy-ə/e-/; attested only in 3pl. keriyeṃ, keryeṃ.
Attested only in acc. ckāckai, du. ckāckane. Possibly /tɕəˈkatɕko/
Root /ɕaj-/, pres./subj. stem /ɕaj-ə-/ ~ /śay-e-/ leveled from PT *śawʸ-ə- ~ *śaw-ë-, with fossilized ptcp. śamāne < (pre-)Proto-Toch. *śaw-ë-manë.
Attested only in acc. pl. pärseriṃ.
Originally *'human' < *'mortal being', derived from (post-)PIE *n̥k̂-wó-. Possibly rather /ˈenkwe/
Loss of nasal between pre-TB *i and sibilant regular here and in piś; see FIVE.
Toch. A ñom points to PIE acrostatic *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥ > PToch. *ñemə, but other cognates are consistent with a proterokinetic paradigm.
From y(n)- 'in' + spe 'near, next to' (analyzed as a "proximative" case ending by Winter (1998:160)).
From intensive e(n)- + tsuwai 'towards, up to'.
In both declarative and prohibitive clauses; cf. Toch. A mā (declarative) vs. mar (prohibitive).
Suppletive stem ṣem- in rest of masc. paradigm. Fem. sana, acc. somo.
Pl. śāmna synchronically irregular. Cognate with Toch. A śom 'boy, child'.
Root /nətka-/, alternating with /natka-/ in the subjunctive and /ñətka-/ in the preterite. Attested pres. 3sg. natknaṃ, beside alternative pres. nättaṅkäṃ /nət-ə́n-k-ən/ to a root /nətk-/.
Early Iranian loan, cf. Ossetic (Iron) widag, (Digor) jedagæ.
Apparent pret. ptcp. of a root /ampa-/ 'rot', but probably borrowed from Middle Iranian
Attested acc. sg. waräñc (with orthographic variation).
Root /weñ-/, weakly suppletive pres. /weṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /wesk-e-/. Cf. Toch. A tränkäṣ ≠ weñ-.
Root /ləka-/, alternating with /lʲəka-/ in the preterite. Pres. act. stem /ləka-ṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /ləka-sk-e-/, otherwise identical to subj. /ləka-/. Iptv. forms to /pəlka-/, cf. Toch. A nonpres. /plka-/.
The less common sārm may have a more general term, 'that which is sown'.
Root /pəja-/, alternating with /paja-/ in the preterite and apparently also subjunctive (v.n. pāyalñe /pája-/). Attested piyaṃ is subj. 3pl.; the 3sg. might have been pāyaṃ*. Pres. stem unknown.

Root /ləma-/, alternating with /lama-/ in the subj. and /lʲəma-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /ṣəm-ə/e-/. Latter widely taken to be from PIE *sed- with *m of nonpres. stem, but source of latter itself disputed.
The less common ewe seems to have the meaning 'inner skin, dermis'.
From tot 'so much, to such an extent' + emphatic particle -ka.
Root /wər-/, pres. stem /wər-(ə)ṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /wər-(ə)sk-e-/. Apparently has both transitive and intransitive meanings. Possibly simply /ˈwər-əʂʂ-n/
The less common auk seems to mean 'serpent, dragon'; it is explicitly contrasted with arṣāklo in B503 a2.
Probably reflects some contamination of PIE *ángʷʰi- ~ *n̥gʷʰéy- ‘water snake, serpent’ with *(h₁)óĝʰi- ~ *(h₁)éĝʰi- ‘(land) snake’; for the contrast, see Oettinger 2010.
Attested only in the derived adjective śiñcatstse.
related to KLOP 'pain' < IE *qlau-u- (= Grk. KLAIOO 'I cry')? (Windekens 1976: 55)
Root /stəma-/, alternating with /stama-/ in the subj. and /ścəma-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /kəlʲ-ə/e-/.
Attested ścirye; i for *ä in initial syllable due to preceding palatal cluster.
Marked far-deixis demonstrative; no equivalent in Tocharian A.
Earlier form ompe attested at B123 a5; also om, especially in late and colloquial texts. Meaning specifically 'there', in contrast to the generic deictic adverb tane.
Root /pəlska-/, alternating with /palska-/ in the subjunctive.
Inherited pattern of suppletion faithfully preserved: masc. se, fem. sā, neut. te (nominal only); acc. masc. ce, fem. tā, etc.
Almost always twe, originally the unstressed (clitic) variant.
Fem. tarya < PIE neut. *trih2 (cf. Toch. A tri). Possibly rather /trajə/
Root /kərsk-/, pres. stem /kərṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /kərsk-e-/. Cf. Toch. A (pärra-)krase '(distance of an arrow-)shot'; wider connections unclear.
Root /səl-/, pres. morphologically causative (with problematic pret. ṣālla, mid. ṣalāte). The rare verb /kərsk-/ (pres. karṣṣäṃ*) has the meaning 'shoot (e.g. an arrow), strew'.
Root /śənm-/. The rare verb /kərk-/, pres. kärkaṣṣäṃ* seems to mean 'bind (to)', to judge from TA parallels.
From *ĝn̥dʰu̯éh₂- ← PIE *dn̥g̑ʰu̯éh₂- by metathesis of place of articulation (see Ringe 1996:45-6).

Cf. klautkäṣṣäṃ 'turns', causative pres. of /klawtka-/ 'turn, become', ultimately denominative to klautke 'turn, manner, behavior'. Etymological connection to PIE *kʷelh₁- likely but not assured, pace Adams. Toch. B /spartta-/ has the more general sense 'turn; concern, conduct o.s.', cf. spertte 'conduct, behavior'.
Originally feminine, from PIE *dwóyh₁ (cf. Tocharian A we).
Root /lajka-/; nasal pres. replacement for PToch. root pres. *ləyka-, cf. Toch. A līktsi, lyīktsi.
Ultimately cognate with PIE *u̯ód-r̥, but details unclear.

from je 'that' (pronoun, not determiner) and -ci. The origin of -ci is the same as in Iron. The pronominal root je is from PIr. *ay-, cf. Av. ayəm. This root does not exist in Iron at all, but is clearly a Digor archaism. Proto-Ossetic apparently had three degrees of deixis; Digor still has them in the determiners (a-ci, je-ci, wo-ci), but merged je and wo into a single paradigm in the pronoun. In Iron *je disappeared entirely.
