Native script: trís (nom.pl.f., Cp 24), tris (acc.pl.f., Cp 35). Latin script: t[riu]m (gen.pl., TB 32), tri]um (gen.pl., TB 29).
Native script: fangvam (acc.sg., Cm 13). Latin script: fancua (nom.pl., Cm 15).
Native script: aapam (acc.sg., Sa 10, 12), aapa[m (acc.sg., Sa 11), aapas (gen.sg. or acc.pl., Fr 2).Possibly not Swadesh term!
Native script: píd (nom.sg.n. CA B 25). Cf. Paelignian pid (nom.sg.n. Pg 4) and enclitic following svaí 'if' svaipid (nom.sg.n. Cp 37) and svaí.píd (nom.sg.n., CA B 15).
Native script: pis (nom.sg.m./f., Cp 32, Sa 31). píís (nom.pl.f., Po 39). Latin script: pis (nom.sg.m./f., TB 8, 10, 19), piei (dat.sg., TB 7).
Latin script: com (TB 15, 23), con (TB 16); very widely attested as a postposition and preverb.
Palelignian 'North Oscan' forms. uus (nom., Pg 9), uus (dat. Pg 9).
Native alphabet: akeneí (loc.sg., Sa1 A 18, B 23), akun. (acc.sg. or pl. Po 44); Latin alphabet: aceneis (gen.sg., TB Pocc.185,6), acenei (loc.sg., TB Pocc.185,9), acunum (gen. pl., TB 31)

To be analyzed as ամեն- amen- 'all' (also spelled ամէն amēn in isolation) with various extensions: -այն -ayn (same as /lexeme/28630/); but also -եք-ին -ekʰ(-)in, -եք-եան -ekʰ(-)ean (the latter two specifically "all (men)", i.e. "everyone".
Traditionally pronounced [jɛʋ]; contrast with իսկ isk 'and; while; but; in effect'
Analyzable as ան- an- 'un-; lacking' (< *n-), աս- as- 'say' (< *h2eg'-, see /cognate/636/), and -ուն -own (if active from *-o-nt-, if medio-passive from *-o-mh1n-, which regularly merged in Arm.).

gloss: 'in order to; to the end that'
notes: Often preceded by վասն vasn [ʋɑsən] 'for the sake of; on account of' (an Iranian loan). Potentially analyzable as z-i, i.e. զ- z- (Nota Accusativi = Def. dir. object marker) and ի i 'thing; matter' (Cf. the interrogative զի՞ z-i? 'what?; why?').

gloss: Orig. "flying (one)"; cf. թռչիմ  [tʰərˈtʃʰim] 'I fly', ultimately from PIE *pter- 'feather'.
notes: Traditionally pronounced [tʰərˈtʃʰun]. Martirosyan derives թիռ- tʿiṙ- 'to fly' /lexeme/1817/ from PIE *pter- (in turn cognate with /cognate/700/) and eventually *pet- 'to fly' /cognate/1486/, see also /cognate/608/.

Also 'to sting'. Often refers to biting of snakes and beasts. Connected with Skt. khā́dati 'to chew, bite, eat, devour', perfect cakhāda (3sg.act.), YAv. vī-xada- 'to squeeze apart', Baluchi khāδaγ 'to eat', Gr. κνώδαλον 'wild or harmful animal', Lith. ką́sti , kándu 'to bite', etc.

gloss: of a woman; fig. also 'source, spring'

notes: cf. Av. ātar - / āϑr - 'fire' (an old neuter in -r̥ ), perhaps also Lat. āter 'black, dark', OIr. áith 'furnace', Welsh odyn (< *āti-) 'furnace', Palaic hā- 'to be hot', etc.
Cf. թիւ tʿiw 'number' from Hurrian tiw- 'speak'.

gloss: specifically "part of day when the sun shines"

notes: Cf. չիր čʿir 'dried fruit', formally compatible with Gk. ξηρός 'dry, parched', Skt. kṣāra- 'causitc, acrid, saline'.
Irregular aorist: կերայ ker-a-y 'I ate', traditionally pronounced [kɛɾɑ].
Probably derived from IE *sn̥gw- 'to sink, fall', cf. Goth. sigqan , OHG sinke/an , Germ. sinken , Engl. sink , etc.
Irregular. Nom/Acc.Sg. հայր hayr, oblique հաւր hawr, հար- har-.
Also variant հեղանիմ heł-an-i-m. Usually derived from QIE *pel(H)-nu-mi (cf. Lith. pilù , pìlti 'to pour', etc.).
Together with t'er 'side', t'er 'leaf' and t'it'eɫ/ṙn 'butterfly'< PIE *pter- 'feather; wing', probably derived from *pet- 'to fly'.

Linked with Skt. meghá- m. 'cloud, gloomy weather', Av. maēɣa- m. 'cloud', Gr. ὀμίχλη 'mist, fog', Lith. miglà 'fog', Dutch dial. miggelen 'staubregnen', etc. Other scholars consider it a loan < Iranian.
Also 'pupil (of the eye); grape, etc.'. From PIE *bud- 'to swell', same etymology as ptuk 'nipple; bud'.
Also 'abundant; perfect, whole’, adv. ‘fully, completely, firmly’.
Also 'that' (with reference to a third person). From PIE *k̂o- along with *k̂i-: Hitt. kā- , ki- 'this here', Gr. κι- 'here, this'. Thus related to /cognate/2435/ 'this'.
From Proto-Armenian *ai̯-s-de (cf. աստէն astēn '(precisely) here; from this moment on' from Proto-Armenian *a(i̯)-s-de-i̯n, with assimilation of *-sd- > -st-). Cf. /cognate/6052/.
Suppletive aorist:  հար(ե)- har(-e)- < PIE *pr̥- of 3.*per-; cf. /cognate/600/.

Also 'to take, have, obtain'. Connected with Skt. āpnóti 'to reach, gain', Av. apāna- 'having reached', āpana- n. 'gain, reaching', Hitt. 3sg.pres.act. e-ep-zi , 3pl.pres.act. ap-pa-an-zi 'to grab, catch', Lat. apīscor 'to reach, obtain, receive, grab', perf. co-epī < *co-ēpī 'to begin, undertake'.
Traditionally pronounced [jɛs]; suppletive oblique stem forms: (z-)is [Acc.], im [Gen.], in- [Abl., Loc., Instr.]

gloss: "in", but also "to" or "from' a LOCATION (depending on case)
notes: Traditional pronunciation: ի [i] (before consonants) and յ- [ɦ] or [h] (before vowels), i.e. as a debuccalized reflex of an orig.  voiced palatal approximant *[j]
Connected with Gr. μέχρι 'as far as; up to, about, nearly; until; as long as, whilst'.
Considered to be a word of unknown origin.
Usually derived from *dor(bh)-n-, cf. Skt. dr̥bháti 'to tie together, tie in a bundle', darbhá- m. 'tuft of grass, bunch of grass', OHG zerben 'to turn about', etc..

Also 'circular'. Derived from PIE *bhel- 'to blow, grow, swell', cf. Gr. φαλλός m. 'penis', OIc. boli 'bull', OEngl. bula 'id.', bulluc 'young bull', Engl. bull 'id.', Lat. follis 'leather bag filled with air, ball', OIr. ball 'body part', OHG bolla f. 'Wasserblase, Fruchtbalg oder Knoten des Flachses', bilorn 'gum (in mouth)', OEngl. bealluc m. 'testicle' < *bhol-n -, OIc. bǫllr 'ball, testicle', Old Swedish bu/olde 'swelling, abscess, tumour', bu/olin 'aufgeschwollen', etc.
From PIE *k̑ō-ro-, i.e. *k̑eh₃-ro-; cf. Skt. śūla- 'dart, lance, pike, spear'; Lat. cōs ‎'whetstone' (< *k̑eh₃-ti-; catus ‎'clever, shrewd' (< *k̑h₃-to-), etc.
From reduplicated *hot-hot-. Probably derived in the preliterate period from the noun hot 'smell, odour' which is connected with Gr. ὀδμή 'smell', Lat. odor, odōris m. 'smell, scent, odour; perfume'.
Also ‘to stay, halt; to stop, rest; to wait; to appear; to dwell’. Widely considered to be cognate with /cognate/2370/ 'to walk, step, go'.

According to Ačaṙyan (HAB 2: 471b), a Caucasian borrowing; cf. Georg. juju 'teat', etc. Note also Hurr. zizzi 'mamma, female breast', zizz-u/oḫḫə , zuzz-u/oḫḫə 'spouted jar', Chechen c̣uz-am 'spout', etc.
Identical to /lexeme/28496/ 'to float'. Cf., byform լողիմ lołim.

Connected with Av. zadah- m. 'Steiß, Hinterbacken', cf. further Skt. hádati 'to defecate', Gr. χέζω 'to defecate' < *ĝhed-i̯o-, -κέχοδα , χόδανος 'Steiß', Alb. dhjes 'to defecate', OIc. gat 'hole, opening', Russ. zad 'rump', etc. (although Alb connection disputed by, e.g. Mallory/Adams, 1997).
From Proto-Armenian *ai̯-n-de (cf. անդէն andēn 'there, at the very/same place' from Proto-Armenian *a(i̯)-n-de-i̯n). Cf. /cognate/6052/.

gloss: Specifically refers to the person speaking, i.e. "this here (by me)"; cf. այդ ay-d 'this here (by you)'.
notes: այս ay-s < PIE *ai̯- (cf. Skt. ay- 'this here; he'; e-ṣá, e-tá 'this here'; OP ai-ta 'id.') + PIE *k̑ó- (cf. Gsg. այսոր ay-so-r).
CA դ- d- sporadically from PIE *t-, presumably due to the lexeme's 'weak' intonational position within the phrase (or perhaps as a clitic); cf. CA դա da 'that' < PIE *to-.

More precisely: ‘to cause to fall, throw down’. Cf. Goth. sigqan. Alternative etymology: ənd and *ke-, deriving the latter from PIE *ges-, cf. OIc. kasta 'werfen' and Lat. gerere , gessī 'to carry on'.
Also 'to go/come back, return; to become'. Stem: darj.
Also ‘to efface, wipe clean; annihilate, destroy’. Derived from PIE present *gwhen-i̯e/o- 'to slay'.
Also 'forest, thicket’. Compared with Lat. māteria , māteriēs 'material, building materials; timber; subject-matter', which is possibly derived from the IE word for 'mother'.

The form is arguably related to (or influenced by) /cognate/145/.  Mechanically, it appears that the reflex of PIE *tuH 'you.sg' was pluralized, i.e. *du-kʰ.  However, such pluralization is unprecedented in the Armenian pronominal system, and it seems more likely that the opposition *du (< PIE *tu) vs. *(ǰ)uk' from PIE *iuH-s /cognate/5822/ (Lith. jū̃s , Goth. jus, etc.) was substituted by du vs. dukʰ.
Connected to Skt. sámā- f. 'year, season'.
mostly attested in the sense of "world", except for the Susa inscription of Darius (DSf 24) where "the earth was dug". Word sign: 𐏏.
only attested as "fear an authority", but there is no evidence that it wouldn't have been used in its broader sense
On the possible phonological/phonetic value of OPers. /ç/, cf. Kümmel (2007) Konsonantenwandel pp.287-9. (attested in names only)
the original word for 'good' i.e. 'vau' (u̯au-) is attested in composita and as the base for comparative and superlative
various meanings: good, beautiful, holy (Buck 1949:1176-1177) [misleading quote, delete this entry and move lexical source references to the other "naiba" entry]
expected aδam; oblique and clitic stem ma-
attested for time, but no evidence that it would be different for space
only attested in combination with month names, but there is no evidence to assume that 'moon' and 'month' would be different
attested in a compound hamātar- 'of the same mother'
this word is not attested in the sense of "person", but it may well have been the case; expected would be tanū-, wich is also not attested for this meaning
attested as "pointy", but may well have meant "sharp" as well
The word 𐏃𐏁𐎫𐎫𐎹 : <hštty> is commonly read as 3pl. hištanti
only attested in the compound asā dāru "stone wood i.e. ebony", as such a loanword with Central Iranic (aka. NWIr.) s, came probably together with the product
oblique stem ϑuva- , clitic stem ta-
this form is only attested in the ordinal number çitī̆ya- "third", its form therefore certain
emended, alternative readings have been suggested
Comparative form. Native alphabet: mestru (nom.sg.f. Va 24, 27, Vb 4).

Native script: avif (acc.pl., Ib 8), avef (acc.pl., Ib 10), avis (abl.pl. IIa 16) aves (abl.pl., Ia 1). Latin script: auif (acc.pl., VIb 47, 48 [two times]), aueif (acc.pl., VIa 4, 18), auuei (acc.pl., VIa 3), aueis (abl.pl., VIa 1).
Native script: atru (acc.pl.n., lb 29). Latin script: adro (acc.pl.n. VIIa 25), adrir (abl.pl.n., VIIa 9, 10, 21), adrer (abl.pl.n., VIIa 18).

Native script: menes (2.sg.fut., Ib 15), benus (2./3.sg.fut., IIb 16), benurent (3.pl.fut., Va 25, 28, Vb 5). Latin script: benust (3.sg.fut., VIb 53), benurent (3.pl.fut. VIb 57), benuso (interpetation, VIb 64, 65, VIIa 2).

All forms found with preverb pru-/pro-. Native script prusekatu (3.sg.imptv., IIa 28, III 33, 35, IV 2), prusektu (3.sg.imptv., IIa 28), pruseçetu (past pass.part., acc.pl.n., IIb 12), pruseçete (past pass.part., dat.pl.n., IIa 12). Latin script: proseseto (past pass.part, acc.pl.n., VIa 56, proseseto (past pass.part., gen.pl.n. VIb 16, 38), proseśetir (past pass.part., dat.pl.n. VIb 44) prosesetir (past pass.part., dat.pl.n., 9x between VIa 56 - VIIa 54), proseseter (past pass.part., dat.pl.n., VIb 20).
Native script: ařepes (dat.-abl.pl., Ia 6, 19, 23, Ib 4), ařeper (dat.-abl.pl., Ib 30, 33), ařepe (dat.-abl.pl., Ib 26, 44, IIa 7), ařipes (dat.-abl.pl., Ib 7), ařipes (dat.-abl.pl., Ia 27)

Native script pir (nom./acc.sg., Ib 12 (2x), IIa 19, IIb 12, III 12, 21), pure (abl.sg. Ib 20). Latin script: pir (nom./acc.sg., Via. 20, 26, 36, 46, VIb 29, 49, 50), pureto (abl.sg. + postpos. -to, VIa20)
Native script: peři (abl.sg., Ia 29, 32). Latin script persi (abl.sg., VIb, 24, 37-39).
Attested in Latin script peturpursus 'four-footed' (dat.pl., VIb 11) < *kʷetur-pōd- 'quadriped' (cf. Gr. τετράπους, Ved. cā́tuṣpad-, Lat. quadrupēs).
Latin script: plener (abl.pl.n., VIIa 21, 34).  Possibly also Paleo-Umbrian: pleno (nom./acc.pl.n.? Um 12-15), but context unclear.

Native script: teřa (3.sg.pres.subj., Ib 34-36), titu (3.sg.imptv., Ia 33), tetu (3.sg.imptv., IIa 9, IIb 21), teřtu (3.sg.imptv., 2x in IIa 40), tertu (3.sg.imptv., IV 28), teřte 3.sg.pres.pass., Va 7), teřust (3.sg.fut., Ib 34). Latin script: dirsa (3.sg.pres.subj., Vb 13), dersa (3.sg.pres.subj., VIIa, 43, 2x in VIIa 24), dirsans (3.pl.pres.subj., Vb 11, 16), dirsas (3.sg.pres.subj., Vb 8), ditu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 10, 16, 25, VIIa 38), dirstu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 17, 38 (2x), 39, VIIa 5), dirsust (3.sg.fut., VIIa 43). Paleo-Umbrian dede (3.sg.perf., Um 11)

Palaeo-Umbrian forms; Latin script: cubrar (gen.sg.f., Um 7), Native script cupras (gen.sg.f., Um 17), cupr[as (gen.sg.f., Um 20). Cf. South Picene kuprí, qupíríh (adv.). Meaning 'good' attested by Varro (1.1.5, 159) glossing Sabine ciprum 'bonum'.

Native script: arvia (acc.pl., Ia 3, 9, 26, Ib 3, 6, IIa, 18, 24), aruvia (acc.pl., III 31), arviu (acc.pl., Ia 12, 16, 23, Ib 25, 28, 32, 43, IIa 6, 11, 12, IIb 8, 29). Latin script: aruio (acc.pl., VIa, 56, 58, VIb 1, 3, 29, 22, 44, 45, VIIa 4, 7, 42, 53). In context this lexeme is usually interpreted as 'guts' (cf. Untermann 2000:125-126) as a part of the sacrificial animal. Alternatively is an etymological interpretation as 'grain' is also possible by assuming it comes from the same root as 'to plough' (cf. de Vaan 2008:56 s.v. arvum 'ploughed land').
Native script: manuve (L.sg. + postpos. -en, IIb 23), mani (abl.sg., IIa 32), manf (acc.pl., IIa 38).
Latin script: mehe (dat.sg., VIa 5); Palaeo-Umbrian miom (acc.sg., Um 3). Nom.sg. form unattested.
Native script: nertruku (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -co(m), Ia 32). Latin script: nertru (abl.sg.m., VIb 25), nertruco (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -co(m), VIb 37, 39).
Palaeo-Umbrian forms. Native script: matres (gen.sg., Um 17, Um 19, Um 18). Latin script: (gen.sg., Um 7).

Native script: numem (nom./acc.sg., Ib 17 (2x)). Latin script: nome (nom./acc.sg., 13x between VIa 30, - VIIa 47), nomner (gen.sg., VIb 54,59, VIIa 12,48), nomne (dat.sg., 40x between VIa 24 - VIa 51), nomne (abl.sg., VIa 17), nomneper (abl.sg. + postpos. -per, 40x between VIa 23 - VIIa 35).
superlative form, Latin script: nesimei (loc.sg.n., 2x in VIa 9)
Native script: neip (IIa 4, Va 29), Latin script: (VIa 27, 36, 46; VIb 29; VIIb 3)
Native script: rufru (acc.pl.m., Ib 24), rufra (acc.pl.f., Ib 27). Latin script: rufrer (gen.sg.m., VIa 14).

Native script: testru (abl.sg.m./n., III 23, IV 15), testruku (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -com, Ia 29), testre e (loc.sg.m. + postpos. -en, IIb 27, 28). Latin script: destram e (A.sg.f. with postpos. -en, VIb 49), destruco (abl.sg.m. with postpos. -com), destre (loc.sg.m. + postpos. -en, VIb 50), destr e (loc.sg.m. with postpos. -en, VIb 4).
Latin script: uirseto auirseto 'seen (and) unseen' (past pass.part., nom.sg., VIa 28, 38, 48, VIb 30).
Native script: kanetu (3.sg.imptv., IV 29). Latin script: procanurent (3.pl.fut. + preverb pro-, VIa 16).
Native script: zeřef (pres.part.nom.sg.m., Ia 25, 33, 34). Latin script: sersitu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 41), serse (pres.part.nom.sg.m., VIa 2, 16; VIb 17, 22, 41 (3x)).
Native script: staheren (3.pl.fut., Ib 19), Latin script: stahitu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 56), stahituto (3.pl.imptv., VIb 53), Paleo-Umbrian form: stahu (1.sg.pres., Um 10, Um 11).

Native script: vapeře (loc.sg., III 7), vapefem (acc.pl. + postpos. -en, Ib 14). Latin script: uapefe (acc.pl. + postpos. -en, VIa 10, VIb 51), uapersus (abl.pl., VIa 9), uapersusto (abl.pl. + postpos. -to, VIa 12, 13). Cf. Palaeo-Umbrian (native script) vape[řia (acc.pl.n., Um 5) < *laped-i̯o- 'made of stone'.
Stem attested in adv. (native script) ulu (Ib 18, Va 25, 28, Vb 4). Latin script: ulo (VIb 55).
Native script: tiu (acc., IIa 25 (2x)), tefe (dat. Ib 13, IIb 24). Latin script: tiom (acc., 33x between VIa 43 - VIIa 36), tio (acc., 8x between VIa 24 - VIb 6), teio (acc., VIa 22).

Native script: trif (acc.pl.m., Ib 24), tref (acc.pl.m., Ia 14, 20, Ib 1, 4), tre (acc.pl.m., Ia 1, 11), tref (acc.pl.f., Ia 7, 24, Ib 31) tre (acc.pl.f., Ib 27, 43), triia (acc.pl.n., IV 2), triiuper (acc.pl.n. + postpos. per(t), Ib 22, 22 (2x), IIb 25 (2x)), tris (abl.pl., III 18 (2x)). Latin script: trif (acc.pl.m., VIb 1,3,19,43,45, VIIa 3), treif (acc.pl.m., VIa 22), trif (acc.pl.f., VIa 50, VIb 22, VIIa 6, 41, 52), trioper (abl.pl.n. + postpos. per(t), VIIa 51).

Native script: vurtus (3.sg.fut., IIa 2), kuvertu (3.sg.imptv. + preverb ko-, Ib 9,36,38, IIa 39), kuvurtus (3.sg.fut. + preverb ko-, Ib 11). Latin script: couertu (3.sg.imptv. + preverb ko-, VIb 47, VIIa 44, 45), couortus (3.sg.fut. + preverb ko-, VIIa 39), courtust (3.sg.fut. + preverb ko-, VIa 6), couortuso (3.sg.fut.pass.? + preverb ko-, VIb 64).

Native script: tuf (acc.f.?, Ib 41), tuva (nom./acc.n., IIa 27, III 32,34), tuves (dat.m./n., III 19), tuvere (loc.abl.f. + postpos. -en, IIa 33). Latin script: dur (nom.m., VIb 50, VIIa 46), duir (dat.m./n. Vb 10, 15).
Native script: vutu (3.sg.imptv., IIa 39). Latin script anderuomu (3.sg.imptv.pass. + preverb anter, VIb 41).
Native script: alfu (acc.pl.n., Ib 29). Latin script: alfir (abl.pl.n., VIIa 25, 26), alfer (abl.pl.n., VIIa 32, 34).
Latin script: com (VIb 52, 55, 57, 58); very widely attested as a postposition and preverb.
Latin script: acnu (acc.sg. or pl., Vb 8, 12 14, 17).
CL ādduwa- and HL átuwa- (adj.) allow to reconstruct a PA adj. in -u̯o- which is the base of a noun *edu̯ol- 'evilness'. The latter is in turn the base of the adj. ādduwāli- (cf. Hitt. idālu-).
cf. also the extension in -azza- of CL, HL ura/i- (n.). Simplex ura- attested 1x in CL [u-r]a-an.
borrowed into Hitt. (v.) marwāi- 'to blacken'(?). Possible IE cognates: ON myrkr 'dark', mjǫrkvi 'darkness', OSax. mirki, OE mierce 'dark'.
only CL; HL áshanantisa- (n.) 'blood-offering'?, gen.adj. of *ashanant(i)- to Hitt. ashanant- 'that of blood'
assured only for CL; HL has- 'force(?)', abl.-instr. "*314"ha-sá-ti-i 'by force' KARKAMIŠ A11c §30. CL ḫāš- without final -t- (cf. Hitt. ḫaštāi-, but Lat. os).
secundary n-stem tītan from *tīta-, cf. denominative verb *tīt(a)i- 'suckle, nurse' of ptc. tītaimmi- 'nurturing', Lyc. tideimi- 'son'. Native script form ti-i-ta-ni (CL) is dat.-loc.sg.

Attested only in HL.; in CL see Sum. DUMU. Common interpretation of nimuwiza- as 'who has no (ni-) force (muwa-)'. Etymologically connected to Lyc. muwẽte- 'descendence', CL mūwa-, HL muwa- 'to overpower, dominate'.  Etymology of muwa- unclear (cf. Weiss, M. 1996. Greek μυρίος ʽcountless ʼ, Hittite mūri- ʽbunch (of fruit)ʼ, HS 109, 199-214).
Only HL: ha-li-i (acc.pl., BOR §11, ÇİFTLİK §17), cf. há-li-ia/iá (KARATEPE, 292); CL UD.KAM-(i)- 'day'. Hitt. attests ḫal-li-i̯a (dat.-loc.sg.) marked with the Glossenkeil.
As a finite verb only HL. CL also attests a participle ú-la-an-ti-iš (nom.sg.c.) 'dead'.
HLuv. suwani- 'dog'. CLuv. only with Sum. UR.ZÍR-(i)-.
HL BIBERE, ptc. u-wa/i-mi-i-sá.  CL ú-ut-ti-iš (2.sg.pres.)
pasūri(ya)-? cf. ACLT: inzagan-?. Semantics unclear. Cf. notes in Melchert (1993a).
ntr.; only CL. Cognate with Gk. στόμα 'mouth' (ntr.), Av. staman- 'maw' (m.). Native script form tum-ma-a-an, assumed collective plural (Melchert 1993 s.v.).
HL ta-ka-mi-i is probably a petrified form (1x, dat.-loc.) 'on the earth' (SULTANHAN § 39). Common word for 'earth' in HL is taskuira/i-. Cf. also CL tiyammi-

HL kwissa- iterative of luw. kuu̯ai̯a- (LIV² 130 n. 5a). Also attested in Hittite texts. See also luv. nahhi-, nahassa- 'fear' and hitt. naḫḫ- 'to become afraid, fear, be respectful, careful' (cf. LIV² 449). Native script form ku-wa-ya-am-ma-an-za (CL) is a participle.
only CL. The word is attested in an unclear text, but a meaning 'to light a fire' for Luv. pawariya- is ascertained. Unclear remains the lenition of the -h- in CL pāhūr.
*-ye/o-present. Cognate with Skt. arṣ- ‘to stream, to flow’.

CL pī(i̯a)-, HL piya-. CL also attests a stem pāi- (3.sg.imptv. pa-a-i-ú, pa-i-ú) whose context also suggests 'give' which would be a more archaic formation (Melchert 1993a:163). Native script form pi-i̯a-at-ta is 3.sg.pret.
Native script form is nom.-acc.sg.neut.  Also found in HL as wasu- 'good'.
CL; unclear. Hurrian loanword. Cf. also Hitt. uzuḫri-. Native script form is dat.-loc.sg.
Only CL. "May not be complete. Luvian status not assured, but supported by following tarrawaūnta." Same lexeme as YELLOW /lexeme/28855/.
only CL. Native script form is acc.sg.
Native script form is acc.sg. Cf. nom.sg. SAG.DU-SÚ.
Native script form is 3.sg.pret. Cf. HL: AUDIRE+MI-(ma)-ti-. Denominative from tūmman(t)- 'ear'.
CL zārt-, HL zārti-. Luvian generalizes the oblique stem, see zart- and not **zir (cf. Hitt. gen.sg. kardiyas). HLuw. attests za+ra/i-za 'heart'.
Identification of lexeme as Luwian not assured, but supported by context, cf. Starke (1990:593) (StBoT 31).

HL suran-. Cognate with Hitt. karāu̯ar / karaun-. As a proper noun, CL attests the abl.-instr. with Sumerogram SI-na-ti. The genitival adjective za-ar-u̯a-ni-i̯a-ti allows a stem form *zaruu̯ar / *zarun- to be reconstructed. HL attests suran- 'horn' "CORNU+RA/I" su+ra/i-sa (nom.-acc.sg.).
Only HL. Native script form á-mu also occurs as mu due aphaeresis.
(LITUUS)u-ni- 'know'; full phonetic writing (without LITUUS) by the attestation of unimis 'known' (1x, seal of Kuzi-Tešub of Karkamiš). Cf. HL uni(ya)- 'id.'.
cf. CL ipalāt(i)- 'sinisterness'. Native script form i-pa-la-a-ti is Abl.-Instr.

gloss: body part, probably leg or thigh
notes: Precise semantics unclear. Only CL. Native script form is abl.-instr.
Etymology unclear. Native script form is acc.sg. (Nom.sg. is only attested as Sumerogram with phonetic complement LÚ-iš).
For the reading of [ᵈE]N.ZU-aš as *Armaš 'Moon(god)' its cognacy with other Anatolian lexemes, cf. notes in cognate class.
Log. MONS. Luv. *ariyatti- also possible (cf. luw. aryattalla- 'of the mountain'). Native script form from ANCOZ 5 l.1, cf. also |MONS(-)wa/i||-ti-i-sa-wa/i-sa in KARKAMIŠ A17c 2. §2.
From *išaru-/išaru̯a- 'right-hand' with dimin. suffix -ila-? Cf. variant išaru̯ai̯(a)- from *išaru-/išaru̯a- 'right-hand' with suffix -ai̯(a)-. Cf. CL īš(ša)ra/i-, HL istra/i- 'hand'.
CL āšša- 'speak'(?) denomin. of āaš- 'mouth'; HL ásaza- is a derived iterative stem.
Cuneiform Luvian. Native script form is acc.sg. For meaning, cf. Carruba in Kratylos 7.65.
The long vowel resulting from the loss of the laryngeal did regularly 'lenite' a following dental stop:(mi-verb) m(a)nāti 'sees' < *mnéh₂-ti.

In CL proper only written with Sumerogram NIMUN, but full writing found in Hitt. u̯a-ar-u̯a-al-la-na-aš (gen.sg., preceded by Glossenkeil). The stem *u̯aru̯al- is also required by CL ᵈU̯aru̯alii̯a- 'god of sowing/fertility' (ᵈU̯a-ar-u̯a-li-i̯a-an, acc.sg.) in KBo IV 11,59.
Native script form á-sa-ta (KARATEPE 1 §31) is 3.pl.pret.act. The stem is more normally spelled with the logogram SOLIUM.
adj.; only HL and only attested logographically 3-zi; however reconstructable on basis of forms such as CL tarrii̯analli-, tarrii̯anali-; HL t(a)risu (adv.) 'three times'.
Native script form la-li-iš is Nom.sg. Also written with the Sumerogram EME.
Stem u̯ār-, -ša is just particle added to neuter singular. Native Script form u̯a-a-ar-ša is N-A Sg.
Native Script form an-za is Dat.-Acc.
Native script form a-ru-ta (CL) is collective plural.
nom.sg. HL: ANNUS-si-sa-, CL: MU.KAM.-iš (nom.), uš-ša-a-ti (abl.).
Only CL. "May not be complete. Luvian status not assured, but supported by following tarrawaūnta." Same lexeme as GREEN /lexeme/28855/.
EXCLUDE. Lyc. B coll. pl. uwadra; thematization of anat. Suffixkonglomerat -āt(a)r, cf. CLuw. n. šuwātar
EXCLUDE. 'belonging to the totality (: punãma- and coll.pl. *punamada-)', suff. -ezi
absence of lenition, cf. pres.3.sg. lati of verb la- 'die' vs. pret.3.sg. lade of verb la- 'release'. Cf. also subst. lãta- 'corpse'.
coll. to *tewe-, cf. tewe ñte 'in sight of' (Schürr 1998:153), adv. ñtewẽ 'toward, facing' < *en+tewẽ (Eichner 1985:19)
onomatopoetic stem (cf. ModEng. daddy). Probably secundary i-motion in Lycian (cf. Lyd. nom.sg. taadaś).
factitive from n. zχχa- 'fight', cf. zχχaza- 'fighter'. 3.pl.pret.(?) zχχãte, inf. zχχãna. The inf. is the given native script form.

Lyc. pije- is the result of the  generalization of *bija- from the 3.pl. *bijanti, see pres.3.sg. *bijati near the form *bai (*#b  > #p ). The formation of the *bijanti is still unclear. This could be comparable to 3.sg. dai 'put' and 3.pl. tianzi, tiyanzi 'they put' - This would mean that the ablaut *o / Ø of the root of the ḫi-Verben (which undergo ablaut) has been used for a verb of different origin. In particular, protoluv. *píi̯ōi is an innovation(cf. HL pres.3.sg. *piyai (: DARE-i), CL pret.3.sg. piyatta) which replaced the old *pṓi (: Hitt. pāi 'he gives') < *pe-Hói̯-ei. Cf. Lyc. pibi(je)- 'to give'. 3.sg.pres. pijeti.
PA *g̑ésro- >> Lyc. izre-, *#g̑_e > #i̯_e > #i̯i- > #i-; attested as Abl.-Instr. izredi
acc.; pronoun -e 'he, she, it'; etymologically cognate with CL, HL, Hitt. -a 'he, she, it'.
EXCLUDE? acc. of *eb(e)- '(this →) he, she, it'.

ebeli-, ebeila- 'hereprobably dat.-loc. form of ebe- 'in this (place)', cf. also ebi(je)- 'local, of this place' from demonstrative ebe- 'this'. Cf. as distal pronoun in the other Anatolian languages: Hitt. apā-, HL. (a-)pa- / CL apā-, Lyd. bis, Pal. (-)apa- 'that' and the corresponding locative adverb Luv. apati/apari 'there'.
iterative verb. 3.sg.pres. tubidi. Corresponds to Greek ἀπόλλυμι in bilingual texts.
dat.-loc.; Lyc. B -(e)mu. nom. ẽmu, emu, amu (with nasal vowel and Umlaut), influence from dat.-loc.
attested only as moon-god(?) in a fragmentary context (cf. Neumann 2007: 20).
only nom.-acc.pl. adãma attested; men-stem reanalyzed as a-stem.
see also emphatic negative nepe 'not' with particle -pe.

gloss: stand, remain, be placed (in a standing position)
notes: Enlarged root *(s)teh2u- in Lyc. tuwe- 'place (upright)'. 3.sg.pres. sttati
Nom.-Acc.Pl. of pronoun -e 'he, she, it'; etymologically cognate with CL, HL, Hitt. -a 'he, she, it'. Lyc. -e < *-oi̯
EXCLUDE. use of demonstrative (dat.Pl.) as pronoun.
etymologically cognate with CL and Hitt. apā- 'that'. PA *obṓ-.
Lycian (A) teri-, Milyan (Lycian B) tri-; attested in derivative trisu 'three times'
Lyc. B *tbi, cf. tbisu 'twice' (: Lyc. A kbihu 'twice').
the pronoun occurs in orthotonic as well as enclitic position.
PA *kwe-li > teli (PA *kw_e/i > Lyc. t, cf. Greek); locative adverb te-li, cf. also ebe-li 'here'
the pronoun occurs in orthotonic as well as enclitic position.
Attested in form of dat.sg. uhi, acc.sg. uhi, cf. Luw. ušša/i- 'year'.
HL; CL nom. sg. anim. tāwīs and coll. pl. tawa
Middle English moone, Old English mōna
Middle English ful, Old English full
also attested as 'woman', but less commonly than wib
< OHG slingan 'to wind, turn'. Very rarely attested nominally TKD.
Another form is qym. Borrowed < Lat cyma 'young shoots (of cabbage)'.
Goes back to PAlb *nera, further connected with Skt nár-, Gk ανηρ and ClArm ayr, all with identical meanings.

From PAlb *ksandā further compared with Skt cándati '(he) shines, is bright', candrá- 'shining; moon'. Regarding word formation, the word is also particularly close to Celt *kando-, Welsh cann 'white' and MBret cann 'full moon'.
The dust that rises from the sand.
Refers to food (meet, fruits). 'spróchniały' refers to powdery, rotting trees or wood.
Depending on the exact meaning forms with various prefixes/suffixes are used ('ścisnąć, ściskać, wycisnąć, wyciskać' etc.

There are more possible variants: 'pchnąć nożem' (formal) 'ugodzić (nożem)' (archaich). 'kłuć (nożem)' (in the context like "He stabbed him with a knife" obsolete too; but e.g. in context of working with a knife in common usage).
Probably the instrument, not the horn of animals. Compare Hitt. šāu̯ītra- 'horn (the instrument)' (cf. Kloekhorst 2008: 540-541).
Holm states this is a 'dansk form'.

Controversial. Either affixed pronoun in the dative (*mī < *moi) or accusative (*mī < *mē). Only in the latter case it would be cognate with the Goidelic and Brittonic pronouns. Alternatively -mi could represent athematic verbal ending -mi. Then, the word 'I' would not be attested in Gaulish.
Attested in many proper names, e.g. Magius, and assumed to be the general term in this meaning.
Attested in a theonym Etnosus, but assumed to contain the basic Gaulish word in this sense.
Attested in river names and other toponyms, e.g. Dubra "the waters" > Fr. Douvres.
Attested in numerous names, e.g. Cuno.
The attested form is 2 pl (imperative or indicative).
Attested in some names, e.g. Suausia ("good-eyed").
Attested in compounds and derivatives, e.g. pinpetos "fifth".
A late Gaulish form corresponding to earlier unattested *traget-.
Attested in many personal and other names, e.g. Uisulanius ("full of wisdom")
Attested form means "has given, has offered".
The Gaulish word is reported by the Roman author Pliny.
Attested in personal names, e.g. Uolto-dagae ("good-haired").
Attested in toponyms and personal names, e.g. Lama-tutus ("right-hand").
Inferred from French hydronyms, e.g. Jouanne < *yag-onia "the icy".
Attested in place names, e.g. Penne-locos ("head of the lake").
Extremely common element of personal names.
Latin bucca is often regarded as a borrowing from this Gaulish word, and the Romance words for "mouth" are descended from that Latin word.
This attested form is plural. (The expected sg. is anuan.)
Attested in derivatives, e.g. tri-noxt[ion] "(festival) of three nights".
Frequent in personal names, e.g. Seno-virus ("old man").
Also attested in proper names, e.g. Allo-broges ("from another land").
Inferred from the compound teuoxtonio- "of gods and men (people)".
Attested in names, e.g. Rudianus (an epithet of Mars), Roudius.
Attested in names, e.g. the common toponym Avon.
Attested as such, and in many compound names.
Attested in toponyms, attested (e.g. Uidua) and inferred (from French toponyms), and in other names.
Attested in very many names and derivatives.
The cited form is genitive plural (the nominative singular would be bena).
This word is inferred from proper names, e.g. the toponym Rusco-ialum, and from loans into late Latin preserved in Romance.
Borrowed into medieval Latin camminus > Fr. chemin, etc.
Inf. πλεῖν. More commonly used to mean "sail", etc., but also "float" (of inanimates in the sea).
Orel gives edhe (1998: 85). dhe reflects IE *do , as preserved in Slav da 'and, so that'.
Also 'thing'. Relatively late loanword from West Balkan Romance continuant of Lat. causa.
Orel gives te, stating tek to be a more archaic form. Reflects IE *toi kuu- 'to that which'.

gloss: crust, tree bark, scab on a wound

notes: Also 'womb, abdomen'. < PAlb *baruka, continuing *bhor-uko-, a derivative of IE *bher- 'to carry'.
fem. zezë; < Pr. Alb. *džedi, connected to MHG quāt 'dirt', OE cwéad 'bad', Lith gěda 'shame', etc.
< Pr. Alb *saka, related to Gk οπος 'juice', Lith sakaĩ 'resin', Slav *sokЪ 'juice' and other continuants of IE *sokuo- 'id'.
Note gji/gjî 'breast, chest' (mainly Gheg), according to Orel < Latin *sina <-- sinus 'curve, fold'. However a loan is doubtfully because of s- > gj- instead of expected sh-.
Goes back to Pr. Alb. *rina. Etymologically further connections to Skt rinati 'to pour'.

Late derivative of ftoh ~ ftof 'to cool, to make cold' < Pr. Alb. *wi-tāja, whose second element compares with Slav. *tajo, *tajati 'to melt', < PIE *teh₂- 'thaw, melt', here with suffix -f- < -h- < *-sk̑e-. The oppositive meaning derives from the preverb f- < *wi- < *apu- (Schumacher & Matzinger: 974).
< Pr. Alb. *dītā, connected to Germ. *tīdiz 'time' and Skt dīta 'brightness, splendour'.
< Pr. Alb. *wausi- further related to IE *ōus- 'id.'.
-zë is diminutive, but almost stable element of the word in Standard Alb.Gheg shows vo ~ ve, which according to Orel speaks for a borrowing < Latin ovum 'id'.
Also 'lard, suet, tallow'. Either (i) < PAlb *dzel-ma, from Alb dhallë 'buttermilk', or (ii) < IE *deh2- 'to flow' > all 3 Balkan IE languages, see also Gk cognate and Arm tamuk 'wet'.
Also 'pair (of oxen)'. Borrowed < Lat penna, pinna 'feather'.
Also 'cloud'. Either cognate with Slav *mьgla 'darkness, mist' or borrowing from Lat nebula 'cloud'. Orel prefers the Slavic origin.
Also 'leg'. Borrowed < Rom *kamba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.
Nor borrowed from Latin, cf. Klingenschmitt, Albanian numerals.
< Pr. Alb. *bara, related to Lat far 'sort of grain, spelt'.
The sg. zorrë, nom.def. zorra, refers to a single bowel, the plural zorrë to 'guts' as a mass noun. < Pr. Alb. *džārnā, identical to Lith žarnà 'id.' continuing IE *guerə- 'to swallow'.
This is the plural of sg. flok 'a hair'. Borrowed < Lat floccus 'lock, flock'.
< Pr. Alb. *a-ei = proclitic particle *a + demonstrative *ei, identical to IE *ei-; or < IE *sa- (following Pedersen).
Also 'bulb, berry, grain'. Borrowed < Lat coccum 'berry'.
Also 'middle'. No reliable explanation for etymology.
< Pr. Alb. * ka tu, including pronominal stem *ka < IE *kuo- and adverbial *tu, cf. Skt tú 'now'.
Also 'as'. Several possible etymologies: < IE pronominal *kuei-, < IE demonstrative *ki- or via Lat quei > qui 'how' < IE * kui-.
Composite form of personal pronoun u (identical to u 'self' < PAlb *we) and particle në (cf. Gk ναí, νη).
Loanword < Gmc (E. Gmc, possibly Balkan Gothic) * jakulaz 'icicle, glacier'. Cf also ON jokull, OE givel 'icicle'.
Orel gives the parallel form ndë. < IE *en 'in' and *do 'to'.
Rather 'foliage, green leaves'. Connected to OHG questa 'tuft', ON kvistr 'branch' and Slav gvozdь 'wood, forest'.
Also 'foot'. Borrowed < Rom *camba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.
Also 'lung'. They can be distinguished as 'mëlçi e bardhë' = 'lung', 'mëlçi e zezë' = 'liver'. Originally 'spleen', borrowed < Ital milza 'id'.
More specifically anatomical term for 'male human'.Borrowed < Lat masculus 'male, masculine'. Also 'hook'.
Also hanë. < Pr. Alb. *ksandā, to be compared with Skt càndati '(he) shines, is bright', candrà 'moon'.
Also nanë. Onomatopoeia, comparable with SCr nana, Rum nană 'id'.
< Pr. Alb. *apsera, variant of IE *apo, cf Skt. àpara 'posterior, later'.
Borrowed < Turk. kafa 'occupit, head'. Rum ceafă is a loan < Alb.

< Pr. Alb. *nuka, composed of *nu < IE *ne and *ka < Kuo-, a pronominal stem. In colloquial Albanian, 's is at least as frequent as nuk. It derives from the full form as, which as such, in the written language, is a more emphatic negation ('not even', 'neither...nor')
< Pr. Alb. *ainja, derivative of IE *oi-no: Lat unus, Goth ains, OPrus ains 'id', etc.
Orel gives kuq. Borrowed < Rom *cocceus, cf Lat coccineus 'scarlet'.
Orel gives also rranjë. Also 'oak'. < Pr. Alb. *wradnjā etymologically connected with Gk ραδις 'branch, id.', Lat rādīx 'root', Wel grwraidd etc.
< Pr. Alb. *krūpā, connected with ON hrufa 'scab', Lith kraupùs 'rough', kraupis 'scab', Latv kraũpus 'frail, brittle'.
According to Orel borrowed < Lat arēna 'id', with Tosk rhotacism (Gheg rânë).
< Pr. Alb. *deubeta, particularly close to Gmc *deupiþō 'depth' > MDu diepde, MLD dēpede, E depth.
Also 'hide'. Derived < lakur 'naked', < IE *leuk- 'to shine, to be white'. other etymologies also proposed.
Parallel form: hyll. Goesback to Pr. Alb. *skiwila, derivative of *skijā > hije 'shadow.
Also 'cane'. Related to Gk σκαπος . κλαδος, σκηπτρον 'staff', Lat scāpus 'shaft, stem', OHG skaft 'shaft, spear'.
< Pr. Alb. *gura, continuing IE *guer- 'mountain', reflexes of which are found in Skt, Av, Lith, Latv, etc.

Orel gives the derivation from PIE *g̑ʰelh₃-u̯o- 'yellow', but Holm (p. 82) suggests alternatively to put it back to PIE *dei̯h₂- (LIV 108) 'blaze, shine', viz. *d(e)i̯h₂-lo-, cf. Alb. ditë 'day(light)' < *dih₂-to-.
A variant is atje: Compound of a- (as in ai 'he') and -tje (cf. tutje 'there, on the other side).
Deictic element *kë < PIE   indefinite/interrogative *kʷu- + 'gender endings' *-i, -jo, -ta according to Holm (differently Demiraj a.o.: pronoun *so- as second element).
Borrowed < Lat capessere ~ capissere 'to seize, snatch at', or < Rom. *capsare based on Lat capere 'to take'. Either way, a loan.
Connected to Lith sprūgstu, sprūgti 'to escape, get out', Slav *prygati 'to jump, to spring'.

Literally 'to take breath', with marr 'to take' and frymë 'breath'. Second element is derived from fryj 'to blow' and therefore related to Connected to Lith sprūgstu, sprūgti 'to escape, get out', Slav *prygati 'to jump, to spring'.
< Pr. Alb. *dega, etymologically related to IE *dhegʷʰ- 'id' and its continuants.
Orel gives nëmëroj 'to number, to count'. Loan < Lat numerāre 'id'.
< Pr. Alb. *p(e)retja, related to, i.a., Lith periù, peřti 'to beat, thump'.
Derived < gërmë 'letter', a borrowing from Anc. Gk., although ssome scholars (e.g. Meyer) prefer a Mod. Gk. borrowing explanation.
Also 'to hit, strike, beat'. < IE *bherH- 'to work on with a hard tool, to strike'.
Borrowed from Balkan Romance with the typical treatment of -ct-, cf. Romanian a luptă 'to fight', < Lat. luctārī  'wrestle.'.
Borrowed from Rom *fluctulare, a modification of Lat fluctuare 'to move in waves, to move to and fro'.
< Pr. Alb. *en-kreinja, related to Lith. krenà 'film, thin skin (on milk)'.
< Pr. Alb. *apa, parallel for IE *ap- ~ *ep- 'to seize, to take'. Semantically close to Hitt. epzi '(he) gives'.
< Lat. intelligere 'to perceive'. More evident in dialect forms, such as Geg ndëgoj, Çamic endiglo and Old Geg (Buzuku) ëndiglonj.
< IE *reu- 'to tear, destroy', cf. Skt ruta- 'broken', Lat ruo 'to fall down, rush down', etc.
< Pr. Alb. *kaksja, related to other onomatopoeic verbs in Skt kákati 'id'.
Variant = luej. Also 'to move, to shake'. Borrowed < Lat lūdere 'to play'.
< Pr. Alb. *stūdnja, etymologically close to Skt tundate 'to push, to strike', Lat tundō 'to push', OIr do-tuit 'to fall', Goth stautan 'id'.
Orel gives thom. Connected to Lat cēnsēo 'to assess, to value'.
non-active voice of ul 'to lower', according to Orel to Grk. eilw 'to shut in, press' and Lith. valýti 'to clean'.
< Pr. Alb. *danja, related to Skt dáyate 'id', dáti 'to cut, to divide, Gk δαιομαι 'to divide'.
Related to ndrydh 'to press, to squeeze, to twist', connected with Lat trūdō 'to thrust, to push, to press on', Goth us-þriutan 'to burden' and the like.
Borrowed < Rom *notāre replacing Cl. Lat. natāre 'id'.
Denominative verb, from mend 'mind', a borrowing < Lat mentem 'id'.
Also 'to shoot'. Variant is hjedh. Connected to ON skjóta, OHG sciozan and other continuants of Gmc *skiutan 'to shoot'.
According to Orel, a prefixial (*ek-?) derivative of thyej 'to break, according to him < PIE *ḱeh₃(i̯)- 'sharpen' (LIV 319f.). Not better suggestion available.
< Pr. Alb. *welwa related to Lat volvō 'to turn; and its cognates.
Also 'language'. Connected to IE dialectal word for 'sound' *golso- and its descendants.

Orel glosses this lexeme as 'fruit-tree, fruit'. In Standard and Tosk often synonymous with dru (cognate/503/) and more and more replacing it (which itself > 'wood'). In Geg, pemë preserves the old meaning 'fruit'. Borrowing < Lat. pōmus 'fruit-tree' (~ pōmum 'fruit').
Also short form ç(ë). "Schwachtonentwicklung" ç(ë) [~ q-] < *Kwi- according to Matzinger (112. 158), + farë 'seed, semen, kin' < *sporHeh₂-.
VAlso 'wife'. See /lexeme/30825/. Related to Gk γραυς 'old woman'.
Orel gives 'forest'. Borrowed < Balk Rom *padūlem < Lat palūdem 'swamp'.
Used in different contexts to tʰəndʰɑ 'cold'. kənkən cannot refer to cold weather, but can refer to cold water, for example.
Deverbative derived from an unattested PAlb *sausa. 'to dry' = thaj, aor = thava.
Orel gives fryt. Borrowed < Lat frūctus 'id'.
< PAlb *mira forming a separate isogloss with Slav *mirъ 'peace'.
nom.def. briri. Related to Swed brind 'deer', Latv briêdis 'elk'.
See /lexeme/30782/ - identical. Borrowed < OHG gibūro 'peasant, villager'.
Borrowed < Rom *manctus, based on Lat mancus 'maimed, infirm', cf also Ital manca 'left hand'.
nom.def. burri. Primary meaning. Also 'husband' /lexeme/30778/. Proposed as borrowed < OHG gibūro 'peasant, villager'.
Also 'man, human being'. Goes back to PAlb *nera, further connected to Skt nár- 'man', Gk ανηρ 'id', and Arm ayr 'id'.
< PAlb *mala identical with Lith malà 'land' and Latv mala 'bank. shore'.
nom.indef.fem. re.Also 'young, recent'. < PAlb *rija, derivative of IE *er- ~ *or- 'to rise, to make move'.
Goes back to PAlb *etera, related to Slav *eterъ 'some, somebody'.
Identical to the noun 'truth'. The alternative word 'drejtë' means 'correct, real', to /lexeme/30802/ straight'.
Based on PAlb *detsa, etymologically connected with IE *deks- 'right', Skt dáksina-, Gk δεξιος, Lat dexter and the like, all 'id'.
< PAlb *luma, identical with Gk λυμα 'dirt' and further related to IE *leu(ə)- 'dirt'.
Participle of the verb kalbem (middle voice) 'to rot'.
Borrowed < Rom *rombulus based on Lat rhombus 'magic whirligig or wheel', or < Att Gk ρνμβος 'top, gyro; bell-clapper (clerical).
Also 'semen, kin'. From PAlb *sparā < IE *sporā closely connected with Gk fem. σπoρα 'seed' and further to *sper- 'to spill, to sow'. Holm suggests it may be a loan < Gk.

Present indivative 3 sg., cf. also dibu preterite 3 sg. 'he/she came'. The paradigm of the verb TO COME is highly suppletive in Brittonic. The forms of the present indicative are based on PIE *h₂ag̑- in Middle and Modern Welsh, and also in Middle Cornish and Breton. In addition to this, Old and Middle Welsh possess compounds consisting of *tu- + bot 'to be' (PIE *bʰu̯eh₂-). The original meaning of these forms probably was 'to be present' (Schumacher 2004, 192, note d), Schumacher 2011, 186). Evans (1964, 133) lists MW dybyd etc. as "consuetudinal present and future", MW dybu as "preterite 2". This additional notion could be present in the OW forms as well. In view of Middle Welsh, the existence of forms based on Proto-Celtic *ag- seems probable. These forms most likely conveyed the basic meaning of COMING, without any additional notions. They are not attested in Old Welsh, however, due to the fragmentary nature of the corpus.

Seems to be the Swadesh term in Middle Breton, rather than squeiaff, squeigaff, Modern Breton skejañ. The latter means 'to cut off, to cut into pieces, to make an incision (chirurgical term)'.The Catholicon translates squeiaff, squeigaff as 'coupper, Latin amputare, cedere'.
Only attested in a lexicographical source (Quiquer, Dictionnaire te colloques 1632 II, p. 39)

gloss: "chest" in both its general as well as specialized senses
notes: Cf. non-Swadesh ծիծ [dzidz] specifically 'tit; boob' and  ծոց [dzotsʰ] specifically 'embrace; gulf' (esp. ծովածոց [dzov-ɑ-dzotsʰ] 'sea bay').
Intransitive verb; cf. transitive այրել, i.e. ayr-e-l.

An alternative lexeme is 'zel' which means, however, 'morally bad, evil' (in this meaning it is used normally as attribute of people, mythological personages and their behavior) or 'very bad, bringing suffering and great problems'.
Only attested in the Catholicon (1499); gloss "cauer, Lat. cauare".

Used to denote a flat nose as well as for instruments like a sword of a sickle.The latter usage is however only attested from Early Modern Breton onwards. If the Middle Breton meaning was 'flat', tougn is not the Swadesh term.Etymology: Like Welsh twm 'cut, broken' from Vulgar Latin *tondere 'to shear' (Deshayes 2003, 728).

Compound di- 'un-' and lemm 'sharp, cutting'. Word is contained in the French-Breton section of several dictionaries, but not in the Breton-French part.Listed as a head-word in GIB, but no attestations are given, so far not in Meurgorf.Check older dictionaries like Ernault, Glossaire moyen-breton.
Listed as meaning in GIB s.v. dall 'blind', but no attestations are given. There is a Modern Breton example for the derived verb dallañ 'to become blind, dull', however.
EXCLUDED. PPP of verb kizañ 'to get dull'.Attested from the 18th century onwards. According to Le Pelletier, Dictionnaire de la langue bretonne (1752) a Vannetais word.

Also taltouzet, PPP of the derived verb taltouzañ 'to become flat, to flaten'For both words, GIB gives Gregoire de Rostrenen, Dictionnaire François-Breton (1732) as a source.There are Middle Breton attestations listed. Check with Ernault, Glossaire du moyen-breton.

gloss: to fall, to happen, to occur, to expire

notes: Light-verb construction: caffout aoun 'to have fear', cf. a m-eux oun 'I have fear' B. n. 728.

gloss: but a small amount, but a small number, but little
notes: Generally used with the verb in the negative of after hep 'without'. Na nep meur guer ne liuiris 'only a few words did I say' N. 1143 (Hemon 1975, 147).

gloss: little, few, small, a small amount, a small number
notes: Contains the negator nep.Can be used as a noun, an adjective or an adverb (Hemon 1975, 145-46).Ex. en nebeut á dezyou ez finissomp … hon amser 'within a few days we will finish our life-time' M. 413Note, that 'few' can also be expressed with a construction including bennak 'any, some, -ever, -soever':Mod. Bret. Eur vag vihan bennag a zo e porzig Oranj 'there a few small boats in the little harbour of Oranj' (lit. there is some little boat…) (Hemon 1975, 142).
In Middle Breton only attested in a lexicographical source (Catholicon 1499).From the 18th century onwards also flojañ.

gloss: to fly, to float (in the wind)

notes: The Middle Breton form is a collective / plural. The according singulative, frouëzen (Gregoire de Rostrenen, Dictionnaire François Breton 1732) is only attested from the 18th century onwards.
Singulative. The corresponding collective is only attested from the 18th century onwards gheaut, gheäot, guéaut etc.The Collective is the Swadesh term.

According to a common opinion, gwer denotes a kind of artificial green, as opposed to glas for natural green.But compare the gloss in the Catholicon (1499): guezr ha glas tout un (guezr and glass all one). Gregoire de Rostrenen, Dictionnaire François-Breton (1732): güezr 'verd, couleur de fougère' (green, the coulour of fern) .
Collective noun. The corresponding singulative is bleuenn, bleuen, bleauenn
Further graphic variants: enff, enf, euf, euff

gloss: head; chief, commander; end, top, aim; person, nobody
to hear; to feel, to smell
notes: Further graphic variants: cleauuet, cleauet, cleauvet, clefhuet
Further graphic variants: ponher, pounher, ponner, poner, pouner
Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system, including the adverbs aman 'here', va-se, aze 'there', va-hont, ahont 'yonder' (Hemon 1975, 125).

gloss: to hit, to beat, to strike; to direct oneself, to go away, to leave
to hold; to keep, to support, to maintain

notes: Consists of the interrogative pe 'what' and *aos, aux 'manner, fashion', i.e. *pe en aux 'in what manner?'
Graphic variant: chacceal. Unclear if this is the Swadesh term in Middle Breton.

gloss: husband, married man, head of the houshold; man?
notes: Seems to be used in the same contexts as priet. The Catholicon (1499) gives as synonyms Middle Breton gour, Middle French homme and Latin vir.
See Hemon (1975, 295ff.) for the distribution of ma and mar: ma is used in negative indicative clauses and in conditional clauses, while mar is used in indicative affirmative clauses.
E before a word beginning with a consonant, en before a vowel.
Frequently compounded with daou 'two', an daoulin, douglyn 'the two knees (of a person)'.

gloss: to know, to be acquainted with, to be able
notes: Compound of Old Breton guid-, Middle Breton gouz- 'to know' and -but, the verbal noun of 'to be'.
Singulative. The corresponding collective is Middle Breton del 'foliage, leaves'(see GIB 419)

gloss: to lie, to be stretched out, to rest, to lay down
notes: Light-verb construction (bezaff 'to be' + PPP gourvezet). There are only few ex. im Middle Breton, cf. pan vez e-n bez gouruezet 'when he/she lays in the grave' Pm. n. 235.gourvezet is the PPP of the verb gourvez 'to lay down (oneself), to go to bed'.

gloss: to live; to nourish, to make live

notes: Singulative. The corresponding collective is Early Modern Breton laou, laöu.
Not the Swadesh term if the opposition man - woman is intended.
According to the Catholicon (1499) synonymous to ozech. The latter is however found in other sources with teh meaning 'husband, married man'.

Can be used with count nouns and with abstract nouns, e.g. cals merit 'much merit', cals tyez 'many houses'. Sometimes preceded by a 'of', e.g. cals a doan 'much sorrow', cals a clevedou 'many deseases' (Hemon 1975, 148).

gloss: beak (of bird), mouth; point, end, summit
narrow; cramped, tiny; neat, tidy, strict
notes: Ex. pan-æ enc e-n hent M. 1734

Verbal negator used in main clauses, preceding the finite verb. Quet 'at all' strengthens the negation and follows the finite verb or the finite verb + pronoun. It is not used where another strengthening word is present, such as ken, netra. In Middle Breton, quet is frequent, but not obligatory.
EXCLUDED. Verbal negator used in subordinate and interrogative clauses and before the imperative. Nac is sometimes found before verbs beginning in vowel.
Un is used adjectivally, unan substantivally.
arall is the reduplicated form of all, cf. Old Breton alall, allall. According to Hemon (1975, 158), arall is more frequent in Middle Breton texts than all.

gloss: to pull, to pull out; to reach out for, to direct oneself towards, to withdraw from

notes: In Early Modern Breton also 'to grow (of plants)' (cf. French pousser).
The Catholicon (1499) translates 'rouge, Latin rubeus, ruber'.

gloss: right, exact, correct; just, fair; regular

notes: Attested twice in the Catholicon (1499). Under the headword Auonn an iffern (avon an ifern) with the French translation 'fleuue denfer' (fleuve d'enfer, river of hell). Under the headword fluaff, auonn is given as equivalent of Latin fluvius, French fleuve.

gloss: road, path, way; way (of doing), method, manner
round; complete, absolute; clear, abrupt, sudden

notes: Rarer then crenn, only one attestation in Middle Breton.

gloss: to rub; to beat, to thrash

notes: Hapax in Middle Breton; the only attestation is found in the Catholicon (1499).
Definition given by the Catholicon (1499): grater, Lat. ruspari, sicut faciunt galline. Gregoire de Rostrenen, Dictionnaire (1732): gratter, parlant des poules, des chats et des chiens.
Seems to mean to scratch oneself.
mask. according to Deshayes, collective according to Meurgorf

gloss: to sew; to fix, to attach, to nail; to pierce, to torture, to make suffer
to sit, to sit down / to be seated
notes: The verb asazaff, attested in the Catholicon (1499)is usually glossed with French s'asseoir 'to sit down'.  Intransitive 'to sit' can be found in "hag e asez a-n tu dechou da doue an tad" 'and he sits on the right side of God the father' (Stokes ed.: Middle Breton Hours p. 6). Triggered by translation? There is no verb 'to stand' either.

Further graphic variants: euff, aeff, nef, neff, neaf, en. Frequently used in plural. All Middle Breton examples have a religious context. The non-religious word Modern Breton oabl is not attested in Middle Breton.

gloss: to feel by the sense of smell, to feel
smooth, polished, even, plain  (e.g. of coat of animal)
notes: Not attested in Middle Breton. Its existence can be implied from the antonym di-leffn 'unpolished, hard' (Hapax, B. n. 577, date:1557). Cf. also Old Breton limn, Modern Breton levn.
According to the Catholicon (1499) synonymous with lampr 'polished, even, slippery'. Le Pelletier (1752) glosses 'glissant, qui echappe des mains, comme une aiguille'.Probably not the Swadesh term.

gloss: any, some or other, some, a certain
notes: Bennac is used in a rage of constructions with different meanings. It's main use in Middle Breton is indefinite: en ul lech pennac 'in some place' B. n. 364. The meaning some 'several, a few', French quelques un(e)s is not attested in Middle Breton. In Middle Breton, ur re bennak means 'somebody', in Modern Breton 'some people' (Hemon 1975, 142f.)

gloss: to squeeze, to press, to embrace

romanised: bezaff / lesell / seuell en e sav
phon_form: ˈbeːðaṽ / ˈleːselː / ˈseːvelː en e saːv
gloss: to be standing, to stand, to be upright
notes: As in French, there is no verb 'to stand' in Breton. IN Middle Breton the concept is expressed by light-verb constructions, combining the verbs bezaff 'to be',seuell 'to rise up' or lesell 'to leave' with the noun phrase en e (he etc.) sav, eus e sav 'in his/her standing'.
Singulative. The corresponding collective is ster.
Only attested in the Catholicon (1499), glossed 'French droigt, Latin rectus'.
The Catholicon (1499) has examples for both meanings of this verb, cf. GIB.
The Catholicon (1499) glosses: French enfler, Latin inflare

The definite article and the deictic particle se constitute a discontinuous marker used as an attributive demonstrative. The phrase consists of article + noun + particle, e.g. an map se 'that son', e-n ty se 'in that house'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system: an ... man 'here (near me) / this', an ... se 'there (near you) / that', an ... hont 'yonder'.

romanised: hennez m.sg., honnez, hounnez f.sg., an re-se pl.
notes: hennez m.sg., honnez f.sg., an re-se pl. are demonstrative pronouns refering to concrete mask. or fem. nouns. They are never used attributively.For abstract entities se alone is used, e.g. credit se 'believe that', nep a goaer se 'whoever knows that'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system.
Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system, including the adverbs aman 'here', va-se, aze 'there (within sight)', va-hont, ahont 'yonder' (Hemon 1975, 125).

gloss: thick, fat, massive; dense, cramped; well

notes: Can be used in the same context as tanau, cp. pemp planquen a prenn faou, moan ha tanau 'five boards of beech wood, thin and slim' P. n. 264

gloss: to think, to think about, to ponder, to examine, to plan

notes: The definite article and the deictic particle se constitute a discontinuous marker used as an attributive demonstrative. The phrase consists of article + noun + particle, e.g. an den man 'this man', an fest man 'this festival'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system: an ... man 'here (near me) / this', an ... se 'there (near you) / that', an ... hont 'yonder'.

romanised: heman m.sg., homman, houman f.sg., an re-man pl.
notes: heman m.sg., homman, houman f.sg., an re-man pl. are demonstrative pronouns refering to concrete mask. or fem. nouns. They are never used attributively.For abstract entities the pronoun henn is used, e.g. Credet henn 'believe this', Ha huy henn na lennas? 'Did you not read this?'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system.
The corresponding feminine is teir, teyr.

The verb has the PPP taolet and is cognate with the noun taol m. 'throw'. In Modern Breton, there is a variant infinitive taoler, taoliñ, not attested in Middle Breton, constituting a regional variety (Favereau, Dict. 722).

gloss: to tie, to tie up, to fasten

notes: An alternative lexeme is 'obrniti'. Another alternative lexeme, 'okreniti', is bookish.
Used in the same context as stagaff, cf. liamet ouch ur post 'tied to a post' Dnal. p. 150
Singulative. The corresponding collective is guez.

gloss: to turn, to come to mind, to change (opinion, confession), to start

notes: The corresponding feminine form is diu, dyu, dyou.
Hapax in the Catholicon (1499), which gives however also the noun huedadenn 'vomiting'.

gloss: to walk, to go, to go away

notes: From pez tra 'what thing'? The noun pez 'thing' developed into the interrogative 'what'.
Pronoun and adjective, interrogative and exclamative.
An alternative lexeme could be 'zao', but it is more like 'evil, malicious' or 'very bad'.
The original meaning seems to be 'woman', but the attestations meaning 'wife' are more frequent.
The original meaning seems to be 'woman', but the attestations meaning 'wife' are more frequent.

G.sg. τούτου (stem allomorphy).  Cf. αὕτη 'she', τοῦτο 'it'.  Used as the unmarked 3.sg. pronoun in the nominative. For plural forms see /lexeme/18950/.  For the full paradigm, see http://ucbclassics.dreamhosters.com/ancgreek/paradigmsU/paradigmtables3BOM.html#par30

'Bojati se' and 'plašiti se' are true synonyms and can appear in identical contexts. However, sometimes it is claimed that 'bojati se' tends to be used with with more abstract concepts and 'plašiti se' with concrete objects.
An alternative lexeme is 'oganj'. It's known by native speakers but it is rather bookish.
N.sg.m. attested in PY Ja 749, etc. See DMic. for full range of attestations. Corresponds to Attic πᾶς < *pant-s.
Most widely attested conjunctive particle.  (Even DMic. does not bother to exhaustively list all attestations.)  Identical with PIE enclitic conjunctive particle *-kʷe.
Adj.nom.pl. comparative form *ka-ko (= Classical Attic κακός). Cf. Classical Attic κακίων
Preposition construed with Dat.-Instrum. in KN Lc 561.a  Cf. DMic. for further attestations.
superlative to an unattested positive form *me-ka [mégas].  Cf. Classical Attic μέγας, μείζων (<< *meg̑-i̯os-), μέγιστος (< *meg̑-isto-).

Interpreted as the instrumental plural of an adjective *ὀρνίθιος (*ὀρνιθίαφι(ν)) meaning 'decorated with birds', referring to the ornamentation of a to-no *θόρνος 'chair' in PY Ta 707.1.  The lexeme ὄρνῑς 'bird' is not otherwise attested in Mycenaean.  Cf. Attic ὄρνις (stem: ὀρνιθ-)  /lexeme/18660/.
Nom.pl. form, attested in qe-te-ro-we 'with four ears' describing a vessel (di-pa) in PY Ta 641.2.2, etc.

Appellative of persons used several times in a formula in PY An 607 (do-qe-ja do-e-ro pa-te ma-te-de), without doubt to be interpreted as πατήρ 'father'.  Cf. https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4349
Attested as an element in personal names, e.g. wo-no-qo-so 'Οἶνοψ' 'Wine-eye' (name of an ox). Cf. Hom. *οἴνοπ- 'wine-dark'. The quantity of the vowel is unclear.
N.sg.m.(?) in KN Od 681.a.  See DMic. for the full range of attestations.
Attested in occupational term pu-ka-wo [puːr-káu̯os] 'fireburner' cf. /lexeme/35448/ and Classical terms πυρκαεύς 'fire kindler' and πυρίκαος 'fire-burner'.  In PY An 39.1, 424.1, 427.3, 594.1.
D.sg. po-de /podei̯/ (PY Ta 641.1), also instrumental º-po-pi in qe-te-ro-po-pi (PY Ae 27.a, etc.) /kʷeteropod-pʰi/ (Instrumental) 'with four feet'.
Attested in compounds, e.g. qe-to-ro-po-pi 'with four feet' (Instrumental pl. in PY Ae 27.a, etc.), qe-to-ro-we 'with four ears' (adjective describing a vessel in PY Ta 641.2.2).
3.pl.pres.act.ind. in PY Ma 365.2, etc. See DMic. s.v. di-do-si for the full range of forms attested. Cf. e.g. do-so-si /dōsonsi/ 3.pl.fut. 'they will give', etc.
Attested as an element in compound ke-ni-qa /kʰer-nigʷa/ 'bowl for washing hands' (KN Ws 8497.β). Cf. /lexeme/35648/

Instrumental plural noun attested in PY Ta 722.2. Generally interpreted as καρα(h)α(π)-φι or κρᾱ(h)α(π)-φι < *kra(h)at-pʰi < PIE *kr̥h₂sn̥t-pʰi (cf. Hom. κρᾱ́ατα). The transcription is tentative: /k(a)ra(ː)(h)a(p)pʰi/
Many attestations. Cf. DMic. for full range of forms found. Also exceptionally also attested in form of pres.act.inf. e-ke-e /hekʰehen/.
Noun attested in KN Ra 984.2, probably in plural ke-ra-a in KN K 872.1.  Generally equated with Ancient Greek κέρας 'horn'.  See DMic. for full range of attestations.

Perfect medio-passive participle, feminine singular, to *kei̯mai̯ 'lie' in PY Ea 801.a.  See DMic. for full range of attestations.  The lexeme is also attested as a finite verb as 3.pl. future medio-passive e-ke-jo-to [en-kei̯ontoi] (Cf. Attic ἐγκεῖμαι 'lie in, be wrapped in').

Not attested as a stand-alone adjective, but frequently attested as the first member of a compound, e.g. po-ru-po-de-qe (PY Ta 722.1), unanimously interpreted as πολυ-πόδει (κʷε) 'with many feet; octopus' (describing the ornamental motif on a vessel). See also in DMic. lexemes: po-ru-da-ma-te; po-ru-da-si-jo; po-ru-e-ro; po-ru-ka-to; po-ru-qo-ta; po-ru-qo-to; po-ru-te-we.

Appellative of persons used several times in a formula in PY An 607 (do-qe-ja , do-e-ro , pa-te , ma-te-de), without doubt to be interpreted as μᾱ́τηρ 'mother' (cf. Att. μήτηρ /lexeme/18822/).  Found in the same tablet without attached conjunction -de in lines 6 and 7 (do-qe-ja  ,  do-e-ra  ,  ma-te  ,  pa-te-de)  Cf. https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4349
Adj. N.sg.neut. attested in KN Fh 362.1, etc.  See DMic. for full range of attestations. Generally interpreted to be identical with Ancient Greek νέος 'new, young'
Particle used for negating a finite verb.  See DMic. for full range of attestations.  Identical to Ancient Greek οὐ ~ οὐκ.
Dat.sg.m., attested in PY Ta 641.1 (ti-ri-po , e-me , po-de 'tripod with one foot').
Adjective A.sg.neut. modifying we-to 'year' in PY Ma 365.2.  From PIE *sm̥-tero- and identical with ἅτερος as found in other non-Attic-Ionic Classical Greek dialects.  (Only Attic-Ionic has ἕτερος.)
Adj.fem.sg.nom. in My Ge 602.4A, etc.  See DMic. for full range of attestations. Generally interpreted as the adjective ἐρυθρός (fem. ἐρυθρά) 'red' in Classical Greek of the first milennium BCE.
3.sg.pres.act. in PY Ep 704.5 (Dor. φᾱσί, Hom. φησί)
3.sg.aor.act.ind. in PY Eq 213,1, etc.  See DMic. s.v. -wi-de for full range of attestations. Cf. Classical Attic εἶδε, with augment, from earlier *e-u̯ide-t.
Many attestations.  See DMic. for full range.  Alternate form pe-ma [spérma].
Mid.part. *torkʷei̯e/o- 'twist' (cf. Lat. torqueō).  Cf. Homeric τροπέω < *torkʷéi̯e/o- (Il. 18.224 ἵπποι ἂψ ὄχεα τρόπεον 'the horses were turning the chariot back again').
Attested in PY Ub 1315.3, etc. See DMic. for full range of attestations.
N.sg. masc. adj. in PY Cn 418.3. Many other attestations, see DMic.
G.pl. in list of offerings in KN Fp 1.10 a-ne-mo / i-je-re-ja 'to the priestess of the winds'
Preposition.  Cf. Old Attic ξύν (Later Attic & Ionic has σύν.)  Attested in compounds, e.g. ku-su-pa (KN Fh 367, etc.) *ξύμπαν 'in total', etc. Cf. DMic. s.v. ku-su-
A.sg. in PY Aq 64.2, etc. See DMic. for full range of attestations.  Unanimously interpreted as *ϝέτος (Att. ἔτος) 'year'.
Noun masc. N.sg. in KN K 873.1.  Most likely to be *ὕδωρ 'water' (Attic ὕδωρ).
Attested as derivational base in adjective ku-na-ja (PY Ta 711.3) [gunai̯a] 'female, feminine'.  The phon. form */gune̞ː/ is reconstructed nom.sg. of the nominal 'woman' on the basis of this form.
D.sg. proper name in KN C 908, generally agreed to be identical with δέξιος 'right(side); fortunate' (as a personal name Δέξιος in Classical Attic cf. IG I³ 1032.429, etc.).

Present medio-passive participle N.sg.masc. agreeing with a person in PY Ae 27.a. Generally agreed to be identical with Homeric ὄρομαι 'keep watch'.  The root is the same as Attic ὁράω 'see' < *ser- 'aufpassen auf, beschützen', but the Attic form is a secondary thematisation in -a-.

Possibly attested in reduplicated adverbial a-mo-ra-ma /aːmor-aːmar/ 'daily' (in KN Am 600.a).  Cf. Hom. ἦμαρ, Arcadian ἆμαρ 'day'.  Cf. expression we-te-i-we-te-i (13x in PY Es 644) 'from year to year'.
Perfect passive participle N.pl.neut. referring to cloths (marked with the ideogram TELA¹) in KN L 647.B.  Derived from *ῥάπτω (not attested otherwise as a finite verb in Mycenaean).

'Planina' is more frequent and neutral than 'gora'.. There are some alternative lexemes. 'Brijeg' and 'brežuljak' can be excluded rather without doubs, as they refer to small hills. 'Brdo' [br̩̂dɔ] is bigger, up to ca. 500 meters of relative height but it is still more a 'hill' than a 'mountian'. 'Planina' is described as everything over ca. 500 meters of relative height (usually with more than one top) and 'gora' is a synonyme of 'planina', normally refering to a 'planina' of an average height.
Oblique stem attested in compound ku-na-ke-ta-i 'hunters' (D.pl. in PY Na 248), cf. Att. κυν-ηγέτης 'hunter' (lit. 'dog-leader'). Cf. Attic κύων, G.sg. κυν-ός /lexeme/18699/
Adj. N.sg. fem. referring to a to-pe-za (table) in PY Ta 713.2, interpreted as πτιλλό-ϝεσσα < *πτιλi̯ό-ϝεσσα.  Describing an ornamental motif.  (cf. πτίλον 'soft feathers, down')
Locative singular noun attested in KN B 7034.  Noun identical with Att. ὄρος 'nountain'.
N.sg. in KN Od 2026.1.  See DMic. for full range of attestations.
Possibly D.pl. in KN Fh 353.  Probably identical with first millennium BCE Greek δέρμα 'skin'.
Noun attested in PY Vn 46.2, probably G.sg.  Generally interpreted as καπνία 'chimney, smoke-stack', a feminine noun secondarily derived from καπνός 'smoke'.

gloss: i.e. 'the Sun' as the heavenly body

notes: EXCLUDED. Besides the 1sg ind. pres. delgīm 'I hold', the 3pl subj. pres. delgint 'they would hold / contain'.
Adjective of material, N.sg. fem. describing a to-pe-za 'table' in PY Ta 642.1.  To be interpreted as *λᾱhεία 'of stone', derived from *λᾱh-.  Cf. Homeric λᾶας 'stone'.

First attested in the Catholicon (1499). See also brumen 'fog' attested in Julien Maunoir, Les dictionnaires français-breton et breton- français (1659), which is considered as the first work of Early Modern Breton. All other Breton words denoting 'fog' are attested even later.
That one which is (very) far away both from the speaker and the interlocutor, which is outside the communication situation.
That one which is close(r) to the interlocutor.
An alternative lexeme is 'ѕвер'. However, it means 'wild, predatory animal, beast'.
An alternative lexeme is 'зол', but it means 'evil'.
An alternative lexeme is 'ладен' [ˈladɛn] but it is more like 'cool'.
An alternative lexeme is 'пес' [pes]. However, it is less frequently used.
An alternative lexeme is 'стравува' [ˈstravuva] which is used less frequently. The lexeme 'бои се' [bo.i sɛ] is dialectal.
Alternative lexemes are 'кружен' and 'кругол' but they seem to be less frequently used.
An alternative lexeme is 'драска'. However, it has a (slight) connotation of 'destroing something with scratching'.
An alternative lexeme is 'види' which is less frequently used.

Root /jam-/. Most likely related to either Ved. yam- 'hold (out, back)' < PIE *i̯em- or the family of Lat. emō 'take, buy', Lith. im̃ti, OCS ęti 'take' < PIE *h₁em-; Plausibly related to /jəm-/ 'achieve, obtain' by paradigm split.

Pres./subj. /jə-/ ~ /jəne-/, latter stem originating in 3pl. *yən → yən-en (Toch. B yaneṃ) with productive ending -eṃ of thematic verbs, whence 1pl. ynem /jəne-mə/, ptcp. ynemane /jəne-mane/. Suppletive irregular pret. 3sg. masa, 3pl. maitare.
Reduced to śire in later texts.
Morphologically causative; cf. cuketär* 'hides (intr.), is hidden'. Proto-Toch. reconstruction unclear; unlikely *(wə)-təwk- (per Adams).

Root /məka-/, pres. stem attested in impf. 1sg. makoymar (B78 a4) with unusual underlying initial stress. Cognate with Gr. μάχομαι 'fight'?

Alternative lexemes are 'порох' and 'курява'. The choice is not straightforward. According to a native speaker 'пил' is the most generic and neutral of them and can be used both for 'dust outside' and 'building internal-dust', although it shows some tendency to the meaning 'building internal-dust'. The other words usually refer to 'dust outside' but are slightly expressive.
'Leg' (and 'foot'). One can find a special word for this meaning in dictionaries (sćehno') but it is not used and in fact unknown to native speakers. Native speakers use the general word for leg.

Both outer and inner part of the body. An alternative lexeme could be 'żywot' but in the first line it means 'life, manner of life' then, the meaning 'body, parts of body' and then 'belly, womb' (referring rather to the inner part).
'Kąsać' is less frequently used and refers to a more brutal act.
'Kry' is the original nominative form, 'krew' is original accusative (that later overtook the nominative role (as in most Slavic languages).

Alternative lexemes are 'ciąć' and 'siec'. 'ciąć' is less frequently attested and attested mostly with prefixes (with some semantic specialization). 'siec' is most frequentlu attested in the meaning 'mow' and in the meaning 'cut' it refers to a rather brutal act.

'Wyja' is extremely rare and uncertain. 'Gardło' means 'throath' first of all, then 'front of neck' and only then 'neck'..
'Pręt' seems to be semantically more complex (it tends to mean 'stick for walking').
Also 'żeńczyna, żeńczyzna', with the same root. 'Niewiasta' is semantically more complex (it refers normally to 'maried women').
'(Ch)robak' is more general, it refers to all small and crawling animals (e.g. snakes), although mostly it is used for insects and their catterpillars.
Synonymes like 'razić' refer to more brutal and violent actions against humans.
'Plecy/e' means 'upper part of the back' and also 'shoulders, shoulder blade, back of neck'. 'Tył' is 'back' in both anatomical and non-anatomical meanings and is less frequently used.
'robić' means 'work, be employed, produce, proceed'. 'dziać' is only rarely attested in the meaning 'do, make'.

There are some alternative lexemes: 'drápati', 'drásati', 'drbati'. However, they are most frequently attested in the context of a more violent act, of animal acting etc.

Both shadow caused by human body and other obcjects like buildings, trees etc. It is also attested in many abstract meanings. 'chlad' (1390, 1410, 1415) means 'shadow caused by a thing (like building, tree etc.)'.
Also 'pěti, pieti' with the same root, often attested in liturgical or religious contexts.

Also 'right' and 'true'. There are three synonyms which can occur at parallel places in different texts (e.g. translation of the Bible). However the chosen lexeme seems to fit the best the general principles. 'přiemý' has a nuance of 'direct'. 'rovný' is used most often in the meaning 'equal, similar'. 'prostý' is rather 'vertically straight.

There are two alternative lexemes: 'opuchnúti' and 'odúti (sě)'. The lexeme 'otéci' is attested in many various contexts (whole body, tongue, womb, limb,  wound, leg, neck, belly, lips, gums, cheeks, breast) and is likely to be most generic. 'odúti (sě)' refers to 'leg, arm, belly' and probably denotes a great swelling. 'opuchnúti' refers in most cases to 'eyes, lips, face' only sometimes to 'knee, arm'.
Possible alternative lexemes are 'ledvie' and 'bedro'. However, it seems that 'thigh' is not their main meaning.

The lexeme 'hoditi' has normally the meanign 'fit, suit' in . There is also a secondary meaning 'hit, hit something by throwing' but this lexeme is not the Swadesh term in Old Czech yet. 'kydnúti, kydati' is less frequented and occurs in the context of 'dung, mud, dirt'. 'metati' is typically imperfective.

The word is attested in a tiny glossary with a Karelian gloss 'belly'. (DND 2004) suggests that it reffered to the belly part of an animal pelt. However, it doesn't result from the source itself. Anyhow, the word 'животъ' (as in the modern Russian) is attested only in the meaning 'things, fortune'.
An alternative lexeme could be 'чадо' 'čado'. It is attested only once in a vocative phrase 'my child!' and relatively late.

A part of a place name. The form 'глин-' 'glin' is a contamination of *gnil- 'rot' and *glin- 'clay'. In the corpus there is also attested the infinitive of the verb 'to rot'.

Anlaut mutation due to analogy with (Std.)Alb. kërthizë 'navel'?Alb. gufë, in turn, must be connected with (prefixed) zgavër (~ zguer) 'hole', cf. zgurdhë 'rectum' (according to Orel and Demiraj s.v. dervied from the latter).< PIE *gerbʰ 'to carve, notch' or *gʰrebʰ 'to dig' (+prefix *eks-)?
