Note the semantic specialization and unclear lowering of the vowel compared to Std.Alb. ndej. Eventually contamination with ndan 'to seperate'.

Extended root PIE *h₁ei̯-k-/h₁i-k-, eventually of the type "facere".Likely also attested in the prefixed variant shkoj 'go, walk' and the unextended root *h₁ei̯- in heavily reshaped vete 'go'.Since both, the unextended as well as the extended root variant survive, a split might have occurred in different positions of the paradigm like the -k- evolving in the aorist or imperative.

Not from Ital. filare since this only denotes 'to 'to spin, draw' but with apheresis from prefixed Ital. affilare 'to sharpen, make thinner, strap, strop' (< *'give the thinness of a thread', Meyer-Lübke 260). Adjective via participle.

Loan either from sédere, sedire 'to sit' with conversion of the inflectional class towards the more productive one in -are; or denominal from setta 'trunk of tree used for sitting', setariellu 'stool'.
Loan from Calab. ad(d)urare, -ari 'to smell' with apheresis. Cf. Std.-Ital. odorare; < Lat. odōrāre.
Loan from Std./Common Italian fumata 'smoking, a smoke; smoke cloud, trail of smoke', a more marked word than Ital. fumo 'smoke' and (virtually) deverbal ptc. of Lat. fūmāre 'to smoke'.
Std.Italian liscio [ˈliʃʃo], Calabrian lísciu 'smooth, sleek, polished; simple'
Proto-Alb. *ambëlt additionally 'prefixed' with të- as in Areberesh t-idhur, ti-timë 'cold', cf. Rohr 2002: 124f. s.v. tëtimpt.
Loan < local Calabrian uχχare 'blow up, swell' with loss of intervocalic /χ/ and compensatory glide [j] + usual loan verb integration via suffix -art-.
Non-active of lexeme/61138/ ljanj 'to wash' i.e. 'to wash oneself'.
Loan from local Calabrian penzara; transition into the productive class of onj-verbs (common in Std.Alb for loan verbs but rare in this variety of Arbëresh).
Extended form of Std. Alb. ky/kjo where this particular formation apears only in the plural and oblique cases. Cf. Arb. kitu 'HERE' for phonological development and morphological composition.
Probably a loan from Ital. rigare 'to draw lines, make lines'.
Secondary feminine formation with generalized meaning of St.Alb. lis m. 'oak, high tree'.
Light verb construction of zë 'take, catch, grab' + udhë 'way, road; journey''

Common Alb. uses verdhë to denote 'yellow', itself < (Vul)Lat. viridem 'green' or Ital. verde 'green' (thus Demiraj 105).Here, virdhe is either a re-loan from Italian (the vocalism could speak in favor of this with Italian closed /e/ --> /i/) or influenced by it.

Connection with vb. Std.Alb, mbështét/s 'to stand, prop, lean, lay down' (Arbëresh also 'defend'); refl. 'to lean onto, lie down'?If so, develpment ë > i in closen initial syllables would be regular, cf. kitu 'HERE' and cluster reduction -sht- > -sh- (cf. ash < asht 'BONE', shupia < shtypia), but the word formation remains unclear (-on < adj. -ënë?), as well as the exact semantic development.

Loan < Calabrian (a)mmucciare 'to hide (oneself)', based on the infinitive.(a)mmuččiare (also Neapolitanean, Sicilian) < *ad-mukkiare, cf. Old Italian mucciare, Old French mucier 'id.' < Old Frankish *mukjan, *mukōn 'to hide'.
Loan from Calabrian adj. fem. (manu) manca 'left (hand)', also substantivized manca f. 'the left one (hand)'.
~ Std. Alb. zhur 'coarse sand, gravel'<-- Lat. saburra (~ sabulum) 'grit, (coarse) sand; sand ballast'.
The form dẅē is more common in list-counting, and a shorter form dwı (with non-fronted w) is more common with a following noun.
The form sē is more common in list-counting, and a shorter form sı is more common with a following noun.

The form šiš, which is borrowed from colloquial Persian, is not often used by the interviewed speaker, but is increasingly used in the language generally, especially by younger members of the language community.
The diphthong-like segment in the first syllable of this word is [a̝e̯] phonetically, and it contrasts with ay [aj] (e.g., xwayšk ‘sister’) as well as ē [eː] (e.g., pēšt ‘back’).
It is possible that the underlying form of the v in this word is actually /f/, since [v] has a very restricted distribution in the language.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form dẅıyēs.

The synonyms galü and halq, either of which may be be borrowed from Persian, are not often used by the interviewed speaker, but are increasingly used in the language generally, especially by younger members of the language community. In all words, the phoneme g in this position (after a vowel at the end of a word) is pronounced as a velar approximant with significant closure, but no actual spirantization.
The word mırk is also used for ‘elbow’, but tends to be used in descriptive or figurative speech; wheras balačaq is more strictly anatomical.
The term dıḷ refers to the upper part of the belly, and also to the internal organs, especially the stomach. The word zıg refers to the belly and the abdomen.
The term dıḷ refers to the upper part of the belly, and also to the internal organs, especially the stomach. The borrowed word mēda is a more exact anatomical term.

The term dıḷu ṛūda (common; influenced by Persian) and dıḷı jıgır (not uncommon; also possibly influenced by Persian) tend to be used in descriptive of figurative speech; wheras nāmzıg is more strictly anatomical.
Some speakers of this variety use the form nawk, but  the interviewed speaker uses nāwk.

Both qwıl and pā are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally) for the meaning ‘foot/leg’. The term pā, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.

The term zānü, which is similar to Persian zānu, is also used other speakers of this variety, but is not often used by the interviewed speaker. The words kaškıḷa and zırānü are both common and have the exact same meaning. The word kaškıḷa is cognate for the word 'kneecap' in other Iranic varieties, for example Bakhtiari kaškak.

Both qwıl and pā are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally) for the meaning ‘foot/leg’. The term pā, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.

The word mēz is the most common term in the area. The word čwıṛ, which is also used by some families, including the interviewed speaker, looks similar to the word used by Lori speakers in the same region.

The term qaḷb, which is borrowed from Arabic via Persian, is a more strictly anatomical for ‘heart’. The older term dıḷ also refers to this organ, but has a broader semantic range and also includes the inside of the thorax and upper abdomen generally, and is also used figuratively as the seat of emotion.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form pyāg.

Both zāṛū and bača are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally). The term bača, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.
Some other speakers of this variety, and especially older speakers, use the form xwayšıg.

The term kwıṛ, which also means ‘boy’, is associated with informal contexts, wheras the borrowed Persian term dāmād ‘groom, son-in-law/brother-in-law’ is associated with formal contexts. The cognate term in this variety, zāmā, means ‘son-in-law/brother-in-law’ only.

The term dẅat, which also means ‘girl’, is associated with informal contexts, wheras the borrowed Arabic (via Persian) term arūs (with the variant ırūs found especially among older speakers) is associated with formal contexts.
Both forms (dwım, düm) are commonly used by the interviewed speaker and other speakers.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form čıŋāḷ.
The commonly-used term māhī is borrowed from Persian. The original term māsī, which is less common, is associated with older speakers.

The word paranda, which is borrowed from Persian, is more exactly ‘bird’; some other speakers, and especially older ones, also use the variant pıṛında. The original term mal is still commonly used to refer to birds as a class, but its meaning can be extended to include other flying creatures, or even certain fast-moving terrestrial animals such as snakes.
Both terms (mūrīž, mırüž) are commonly used by the interviewed speaker and other speakers.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form kwıḷāždwım.
Another term, hēzım, refers to sticks gathered for firewood.
The distribution of ŋ in this monosyllabic word suggests that it is a phoneme in this variety. Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the forms waḷg and baḷg.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form āsāra.
The term šın refers to ‘fine gravel’.
The word tūz is a general term for dust, including dust in the air. The term gart is reserved for a 'dusting', i.e., a layer of dust on a surface.
Final syllable with the vowel ı is unstressed here, cf. ‘fire’, where it is stressed. Some other speakers say wafr.

The synonymous terms hawz and gwıḷam both refer to small, seasonal lakes, which are the only type of lake in the region. The term daryāča has been recently borrowed from Persian, but corresponds more closely to the CoBL meaning of ‘lake’, so it is given here.
Final syllable with the vowel ı is stressed here, cf. ‘snow’ where it is unstressed.

There is not a clear phonetic or phonological y between the vowels in pāīz. The term pāīz, which means ‘autumn (September, October, November)’ in Persian, refers to the months of July, August, and September in this variety. There is another word for ‘late fall’ in this variety, also distinct from the word for ‘winter’. The term tāwısān (or the more closely Persian form tābısān) is more common in formal contexts, and among educated and younger speakers.

The word māḷ is commonly used, but its meaning extends to a residence generally, and can also be used for tents where nomads live. The word xānıg necessarily refers to a house constructed with hard materials.
The word pīya (which has the form pī for some people) refers to solid animal fat, and the word ṛün refers to grease (liquid animal fat) or oil.
Both terms (kẅana, kwāna) are commonly used. The term kwāna is more common in formal contexts, and among educated and younger speakers.
This word is two syllables in the speaker’s variety, with no clear glide between the vowels. Some other speakers pronounce it as a single syllable: qaẅn.
Both forms (nāzık, nāzıg) are commonly used. The term nāzıg is more common in formal contexts, and among educated and younger speakers.
The term dwırıs is used for the meaning true/correct (vs. false/incorrect), and the term ṛās is used for the meaning true (vs. untrue/a lie).
Some other speakers say sawnz for this word.
Both terms (čarmıg, sıfēd) are commonly used. The term sıfēd (which resembles Southwestern Iranic spēd/sefid) is more common in formal contexts, and among educated and younger speakers.
The g at the end of this verb form is never dropped.

The forms given here are simple past, not progressive past (which would add dāšt, and sometimes a dı- prefix, before the verb). The present form of this verb (and many other vowel-final present verbs) can also end in a postvocalic g.

The forms given here are simple present, not progressive present (which would add dērē, and sometimes a dı- prefix, before the verb). The final vowels in all such forms are unstressed and non-syllabic. The initial d- is found in the basic present form for this verb (cf. its use on other verbs to mark progressive aspect explicitly). A form yāē is attested in other varieties, however. The present form of this verb (and many other vowel-final present verbs) can also end in a postvocalic g.
The alternate term pılē dā gives the idea of rolling something.
The form xıṛē dā, where the object is explicitly mentioned, is more typical; however, we give the bare form here.
The final vowels in all such forms are unstressed and non-syllabic.
Both terms (dırīžaw büẅü, ıḷāžıyāü) are commonly used, and the meaning is the same.
Both terms (dırīžaw büẅa, ıḷāžıyāga) are commonly used, and the meaning is the same.
The term pyāda čıg means ‘went on foot’.
The two forms, dawī and dawıs, are equivalent and both are used commonly by speakers.
The equivalent terms ežnawē and ešnawē are used by some other speakers. (It looks as if the onset žn is simplified to ž. However, one would rather expect the emergence of an anaptyctic vowel.)
This and many (perhaps all) of the other vowel-final present verbs can also end in a postvocalic g.

The form büẅē, which seems to be the original form, means ‘was’ / ‘was alive [at a certain time]’ / ‘was living [in a certain place]’. The newer form zındıgī kırd is likely modelled on Persian, and its meaning is more specific (but still includes elements beyond the Swadesh definition). Both forms are commonly used. The word zındaü means ‘s/he was alive (i.e., not dead)’.

The form hasē, which seems to be the original form, means ‘is’ / ‘is alive [at a certain time]’ / ‘is living [in a certain place]’. The newer form zındıgī kē is likely modelled on Persian, and its meaning is more specific (but still includes elements beyond the Swadesh definition). Both forms are commonly used.
The progressive/dynamic form is hā xāw.
Both forms (hınās k., nafas k.) are commonly used; nafas is more common in formal contexts and among younger and educated speakers.
Both forms (hınās k., nafas k.) are commonly used; nafas is more common in formal contexts and among younger and educated speakers.

The term pıf is used to mean both ‘blow’ and ‘swell’.

Both terms (with pınam- and pıf) are commonly used.
Both forms (hıq, ısıfırāq) are commonly used; ısıfırāq is more common in formal contexts and among younger and educated speakers.
Both forms (hıq, ısıfırāq) are commonly used; ısıfırāq is more common in formal contexts and among younger and educated speakers.
The closely related word tırsyā, which is a cognate with Persian tarsidan ‘be afraid’, in this variety has more of a meaning ‘be a coward’.
The word čıṛī means ‘sing’ generally, and the newer term xwanıs, modelled on Persian, refers to singing something that has words.
The word čıṛē means ‘sing’ generally, and the newer term xwanıs, modelled on Persian, refers to singing something that has words.

Same verb as 'take'. The term hēz dā has the idea of lifting and carrying. The term aḷgirt bird refers to picking up and carrying something away. A b-initial form (baē) is also used by some people.

The term yax nā refers to the weather or the land freezing, but yax kırd is used for the freezing of water specifically. We retain the latter term based on the guidance of the Swadesh meaning in the CoBL materials.

Attested in the Catholicon (1499), equivalent of Middle French riuyere, fleuve and Latin rivus. The latter denotes both brooks and streamlet and big rivers leading to the sea (cf. German Strom). The Latin examples translated into French all mention bigger rivers, cf. hic geon 'cest le fleue de paradis terrestre', hic padus 'ung fleuue' (Po), hic remis 'la riuiere de rin' (Rhine), hoc rodanū 'la riuiere de rosne' (Rhône).Quiquer's dictionary 'Nomenclator' (1633) only gives riffier 'river', none of the other Breton words.

The Catholicon does not mention OBr. staer, ModBr. stêr, which is used in Leoneg and the Literary Standard. Quiquer's dirctionary 'Nomenclator' (1633) has both riffier 'fleuve, rivière' and gouaz-dour 'un ruisseau', bot none of the other terms. Maunoir's dictionary from 1659 gives riuier and ster for French rivière in addition to ster in the meaning of lavoir.

Although also the name of the internal organ 'stomach', in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the word 'stomach' has broadened to refer to the abdomen in general, and is has become the default, unmarked word for the target sense here.  The lexeme 'belly' is more marked in register, often with overtones of a protruding 'pot belly'..

This may strike speakers of many varieties of English as unusual, but needs to be seen in the context of significant differences between different varieties of English worldwide.  Highly relevant is that in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the lexemes 'ill' and 'unwell' are very widely used, where other varieties use 'sick'.  This allows a particular usage of '(being) sick', in the specific sense of vomiting, especially in the most common aspectual and tense uses.  So in this specific variety, in the default, unmarked register, speakers most often use formulations like "S/he has been sick" to mean not "S/he has been ill" (as they would normally refer to a period of ill health), but to mean specifically "S/he has (just) vomited":  Likewise, normal usage would be: "Please stop the car, I’m going to be sick.", meaning specifically that the speaker felt s/he was about to vomit.The lexeme 'vomit' in this variety has rather narrower register uses, slightly elevated ad 'medical'.  There are also a host of other familiar register lexemes, as in other varieties of English.

“bagàj” is properly “boy/young adult”, but is used by parents to refer to their offspring even when well into adulthood (in one instance, refering to a 70-year-old). The use of words related to Italian “figlio” was considered unnatural by some speakers. The feminine is “tùSa”; I could not find a clear etymology for the word, but considering that it means “(field) servant” in Bergamo, the proposal by Luigi Pavia in “Sulla parlata milanese e suoi connessi” that it comes from a Celtic “bagwall” meaning “servant” and extended to “(my) child” seems acceptable.
Mostly with a preposition such as “burlàa gìu”, “burlàa föra”, “burlàa den”, etc.
All informants gave “có” and “crápa” as equally frequent synonyms. As the second (but not the first) can also mean “skull”, I am reporting “có” as the main one.

Also as “butùn del ventàr”, to distinguish from clothes’ buttons. Some informants reported “bamburìn”, but others said this is not the word in Carugatese, but only in Milanese proper (that is, from the city of Milan); Milanese dictionaries, in fact, list “bamburìn”, and as such I am reporting “butùn” as the main one.

The protetic s- is typical of Milanese and does not (necessarily) carry the meaning of reversal as in Florentine/Italian (e.g., sgonfiare/gonfiare). The issue was sometimes proudly mentioned as an example of the difference between Milanese and Florentine, as in Banfi (1843, p. xxviii: “E però tra noi sconfià, significa gonfiare, tra I Fiorentini sgonfiare, suona l’opposto”)
No single word; informants complained that people influenced by Italian say “vomitàa”, which “is not a native word”.
Sometimes rendered as “viàlter” or “viàltar”, not clear if in free variation or complementary distribution based on euphonics.
All informants gave “có” and “crápa” as equally frequent synonyms. As the second (but not the first) can also mean “skull”, I am reporting “có” as the main one.

Also as “butùn del ventàr”, to distinguish from clothes’ buttons. Some informants reported “bamburìn”, but others said this is not the word in Carugatese, but only in Milanese proper (that is, from the city of Milan); Milanese dictionaries, in fact, list “bamburìn”, and as such I am reporting “butùn” as the main one.

The interchangeable verbal nouns cur and coyrt have both been entered into the database, as Manx expresses the present (3rd sg.) with be + verbal noun. Most forms in the paradigm of this verb reflect those of Old Irish do·beir (cf. Irish tabhair), but cur is suppletive (cf. Irish cur). Coyrt is considered cognate with tabhairt (hence assigned to the same set as Irish tabhair) but with interference from cur in the onset.
